<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Doctor Invents Artificial Human Bones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A Kuwaiti doctor has invented
artificial bones, which he claimed could replace human bones and
extend the bone length of short and disabled people.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Yousuf Ali Al-Bader said he created a kind of substance
which has the same features of human bones, the Kuwait News Agency
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The substance can be used as a substitute to human bones
because it can easily heal, grow and be part of the human body,
said the doctor.
</P>
<P>
"It has no side effects and does not need adhesive materials
or nails to fix with natural bones because it is very flexible to
merge and allows the growth of huge new cells and by time will
become part of the bones," Bader added.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti doctor, who carried out four years of research in
Britain, the United States and France, has also found that his
invention could help treat fractures among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
"This way will have good effects in helping prolong the short
and disabled people at a certain age," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bader, based on his invention, also rejected a common belief
that milk was the only means to strengthen bones.
</P>
<P>
Following a study on reasons behind bone diseases, the doctor
found that diseases like pains of joints, rheumatism,
osteomyelitis and reduction of vertebrae resulted from the
consumption of milk and its by-products.
</P>
<P>
He said that people depend on milk to get the necessary
calcium to strengthen bones, but milk also causes problems in
human's digesting system and colon due to its fermentation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
