<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economic Growth Seen to Outperform Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's economy could
outperform the government's current official forecast of zero to 2
percent for 1999, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lee told the parliament that the government will review its
current forecast in August as there are signs that the economy has
been recovering faster than expected.
</P>
<P>
"The economy has been recovering well this year," Lee said.
"Recent data suggest the economy might outperform the government's
current forecast."
</P>
<P>
He attributed the unexpectedly strong recovery to a growth in
global electronics demand and the region's overall rebound from
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the manufacturing sector, which grew by 8.2 percent in
the first five months of this year, led Singapore's economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
Indicators from other sectors of the economy showed that the
recovery was becoming broad-based although not every sector was
doing well, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government may restore part of the 10
percentage point cut in the Central Provident Fund (CPF) for
employees next year if the economic recovery continues to gain
momentum.
</P>
<P>
A decision will be made by the government at the end of this
year when this year's economic performance and the outlook for
next year are known, he added.
</P>
<P>
The employers' CPF contribution was cut for a period of two
years from January this year as part of a package to reduce
business costs.
</P>
<P>
"Of all the measures we took, the CPF cut had the most impact
on our business costs and contributed significantly to the current
recovery," he said.
</P>
<P>
If wage settlements are allowed to go up too quickly now, said
Lee, the effects of the CPF cuts will be negated, making it more
difficult to restore CPF contribution rates later on.
</P>
<P>
"However we recognize that in a strong recovery, wage pressures
are unavoidable," said the deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore if the recovery continues to gain momentum, it will
be better to manage these pressures, by beginning to restore the
employers' CPF contribution earlier, while continuing to exercise
restraint in wage settlements," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the other cuts in government rates, rentals and taxes
and rebates, the stipulated periods will remain and be reviewed
later, said Lee.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore economy grew by a modest 1.2 percent in the first
quarter of this year, largely on the back of a strong performance
in the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
From April to May, shares transacted grew 270 percent in value
and 390 percent in volume.
</P>
<P>
Visitor arrivals also grew 7.2 percent from January to May,
compared with double-digit drops last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
