<HEADLINE> Thailand Open Draws Top Shuttlers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Grand Prix Thailand Open
Badminton Championships was inaugurated here Tuesday with the
participation of the world's top three players, Peter Gade-
Christensen, Sun Jun and Fung Permadi.
</P>
<P>
However, world No.1 Christensen has decided to take part only
in the men's doubles, since Thailand Open is just a three-star
event.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the 22-year-old Sun Jun of China, who won World
Grand Prix in Bandar Seri Begawan and the World Championships in
Copenhagen in May, was top seed in the men's singles, followed by
Chinese Taipei's Fung, runner-up to Sun in the world meet.
</P>
<P>
As for the lady's singles, China's Dai Yun, ranked world No. 2,
was seeded top while world No. 3 and compatriot Gong Ruina is
second.
</P>
<P>
The first day of the match saw no big surprises, with most of
the seeds easily moving to the second round.
</P>
<P>
The 80,000-U.S. dollar championship is expected to end on
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
