<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Students Protest French Support for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A group of Iranian students on
Tuesday gathered in front of the French embassy to protest against
the support of French Parliament Speaker Laurent Fabius for the
13 Iranian Jews arrested on espionage charges.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to French President Jacques Chirac, the
demonstrators called on Fabius to officially apologize to Iran,
the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In the letter submitted to the French ambassador to Tehran,
the students stated that Iran would not accept any foreign
interference in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
They also underlined that the 13 Iranian Jews had been
arrested on espionage charges, not for their religious faith,
IRNA said. But it did not mention the number of the protesters.
</P>
<P>
Fabius told the French National Assembly last Wednesday that the
Iranian Jews were arrested for being Jews and would face the
death penalty by hanging "on unfounded charges."
</P>
<P>
One hundred and forty-three French parliamentarians recently
also voiced their support for the Iranian Jews and urged the
French government to reconsider its relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Majlis (parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri on
Sunday also dismissed the stance of Western countries on the issue
as "a blatant interference and meddling" in Iran's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
No one is being prosecuted in Iran for advocating certain
belief or religion, said the speaker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Call for Common Stock Market in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Participants attending the
World Economic Forum's southern African summit in Durban Tuesday
called for a common stock market and a single currency for the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) region.
</P>
<P>
Russell Loubser, President of the Johannesburg Stock Exchange,
said that a common trading platform is necessary for the region,
similar to the one that already existed between Namibia and South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Regional markets must continue to develop but not at the
expense of liquidity. Global and sectoral industries will assume
more importance," Loubser said in a statement available here.
</P>
<P>
Both Loubser and Jacko Maree, Managing Director of Standard
Bank of South Africa, called for projects aimed at developing a
core of professionals in the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The call was echoed by South African Finance Director-General
Maria Ramos, who said the architecture of capital markets needed
to be considered.
</P>
<P>
"Capacity is not just about developing existing capacity, but
broadening capacity," Ramos told the summit. She said the issue
of "dead management" needed to be addressed pro-actively.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot keep chasing the same group of people. We need to
broaden that skills group," she said
</P>
<P>
"As a seeker of capital, southern African markets cannot make a
good impression once. We have to continually work on the
relationship with the investors," she said.
</P>
<P>
Loubser and Egas Mussanhane, Chairman of the Economic
Associations Commission of Mozambique, told a workshop that the
region must succeed in securing local investment and domestic
savings.
</P>
<P>
Loubser added that exchange controls needed to go and that
industrial relations harmony and a sound and fair regulatory
environment were important to attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Rocco Rossow, Managing Director of the African Banking Group,
said universal adoption of international accounting standards in
the region, a common currency and consolidated supervision for the
financial services sector are necessary.
</P>
<P>
Also necessary is the harmonization between fiscal and monetary
policies.
</P>
<P>
But former South African Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg
opposed the concept of a common currency at this stage.
</P>
<P>
"If one looks at the European Union, you first had the free
movement of goods, capital and currency before a common currency
was developed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Current Finance Minister Trevor Manuel shared the sentiment,
saying that a common currency was less important at present than
minimizing costs was.
</P>
<P>
He said there is insufficient economic convergence to have a
common currency and that over-extension in this regard could be
counter-productive.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Botswanan central bank, Baledzi Gaolathe, also
said he believed that in the short term the reduction of financial
transaction costs is more important than a common currency.
</P>
<P>
SADC executive Kaire Mbuenda said he was convinced that a
single currency for the region would be established, but also felt
that other issues were more important before regional trade
integration could become a reality.
</P>
<P>
Manuel told a news conference Tuesday that whereas politics had
 dominated previous summits, this year's summit has largely
focused on investment and sustainable economic growth in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
