<HEADLINE> Durban to Host Southern African Economic Summit in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The South African city of
Durban will again host next year's annual World Economic Forum
southern African summit, organizers announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at the close of this year's three-day
summit in Durban, which drew more than 850 political and business
leaders, mostly from southern Africa, the United States and some
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Durban, south of Johannesburg, is marketing itself as the
premier convention city in the country. Its International
Convention Center has already attracted major conferences,
including the Non-Aligned Movement summit last November.
</P>
<P>
Later this year, Commonwealth heads of state will also gather
here.
</P>
<P>
World Economic Forum organizers said next year's summit would
include other African countries and major business people from
outside the region.
</P>
<P>
The proposed date is from June 21 to 23, 2000, and the summit
would allow delegates to "collectively kick off the African
century", according to South African Press Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
