<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Vows to Reach Comprehensive Peace with Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Incoming Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak Tuesday pledged to work to achieve a comprehensive
peace with all of Israel's Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"I called on all regional leaders to take our outstretched
hand and to make a peace of the brave in the area," Barak said
before presenting his coalition to the Knesset, or parliament,
for approval.
</P>
<P>
Winning the May election on a platform to revive the peace
process on all tracks, Barak reiterated that peace will be the top
priority of his new government.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent bid to ease fears of the Palestinians and
Syrians that they might be played against each other while Barak
resumed the stalled peace talks with them, the ex-army chief said
peace with Arab neighbors are "equally vital" to Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The reaching of a permanent agreement with the Palestinians
and the achieving of peace with Syria and Lebanon are equally
vital and urgent in my eyes," he said.
</P>
<P>
After winning the May elections, Barak and Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad have, through indirect channels, exchanged messages
of mutual trust and intentions to revive the peace talks, which
broke off three years ago.
</P>
<P>
These signs, together with Barak's promise to pull Israeli
troops from south Lebanon within a year, raised concerns among the
Palestinians that they might be left behind.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the parliament, Barak said he understands not
only the suffering of the Israeli people but also that of the
Palestinians and would work for peace with them.
</P>
<P>
"I want to work with the elected Palestinian leadership headed
by Yasser Arafat in a friendship and partnership in order to
achieve a proper co-existence," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Syrian track, Barak appealed to Assad to move quickly
to forge peace with his new government.
</P>
<P>
"The new government of Israel is determined to advance
negotiations as quickly as possible to achieve a full bilateral
agreement on peace and security based on (U.N.) Security Council
resolutions 242 and 338," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two resolutions call for Israel to withdraw from Arab
lands occupied in the 1967 Middle East war, including the Syrian
territory of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
"We have been very determined force in the battle of
peace...it is about time to come to achieve open and courageous
peace to make sure the future and security of ourselves, our
children and our grandchildren," he said.
</P>
<P>
"No force will prevent us from achieving our goal of peace,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qureia welcomed
Barak's remarks, saying that the Palestinians are "cautiously
optimistic that this government will work toward advancing the
peace process."
</P>
<P>
After more than six weeks of grueling talks, Barak put
together a coalition comprising of seven parties in the
15-faction Knesset, securing a majority of 75 seats, the largest
majority in the 120-member Knesset in Israel in years.
</P>
<P>
With most of his coalition partners favoring or holding
neutral attitude toward peace, confidence has grown among the
Arab world that Barak might be able to move forward the
peace process quickly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
