<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Lebanese Banks Merged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Banque Libanaise pour le
Commerce (BLC) and the United Bank of Lebanon (UBL) Tuesday signed
a merger agreement, Lebanon's independent Central News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
BLC will buy out UBL's assets to form a new bank with the name
of UBL, said a joint statement issued by Chairman of BLC Felix
Jean Aboujaoude and his UBL counterpart Safi Harb at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
"The merger will create a new financial power in the banking
sector which enjoys high potential for development locally and
regionally," Aboujaoude said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, UBL's capital will be raised to about 250
million U.S. dollars from 60 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total assets of the amalgamated banks will be more than 1.5
billion dollars, making UBL among the country's five top banks.
</P>
<P>
The new bank's branches will also rise to 47 with four in the
United Arab Emirates and one in France.
</P>
<P>
Shares of BLC, which is the first bank in Lebanon to be listed
on the Beirut Stock Exchange, will continue to be traded, the
statement said, adding that the merger will have to be approved
by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly 80 banks in Lebanon, most of them are small
and family-run businesses.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has been offering incentives to facilitate
takeovers in the banking sector, which analysts say is too
crowded, but only a handful of banks have taken advantages of the
break. 
</P>
</TEXT>
