<HEADLINE> Clinton Imposes Sanctions on Afghanistan's Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
signed an executive order imposing financial sanctions against
Afghanistan's Taliban in retaliation for its support of Osama bin
Laden, a senior administration official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden, who the United States alleged was responsible for
the bombing of its two embassies in African, was placed on the
FBI's "Ten Most Wanted List" last month with a 5 million U.S.
dolllars reward offered for information leading to his arrest.
</P>
<P>
The senior official said the president's action sends a clear
message that the United States would not tolerate those who
support bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
The United States demands that the Taliban expel bin Laden to
the United States for trial or to a third country where he would
face justice for alleged bombing.
</P>
<P>
Taliban leaders have insisted they do not know where bin Laden
is.
</P>
<P>
The president's executive order freezes any property of the
Taliban within U.S. jurisdiction. It also prohibits transactions
and trade with the Taliban or in territory controlled by the
Taliban, preventing any U.S. investment. U.S. trade with
Afghanistan totaled 24 dollars million in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
