<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 23 Countries Sign on New Act to Protect Industrial Designs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- 23 countries signed here Tuesday on
a new act to broaden the geographical scope of international
industrial design protection adopted by consensus on July 2 at the
end of the diplomatic conference of the World Intellectual
Property Organization (WIPO).
</P>
<P>
According to a WIPO press release, the delegations signed the
Geneva Act of the Hague Agreement Concerning the International
Registration of Industrial Designs are Algeria, Belgium, Bulgaria,
Chad, Croatia, Cuba, Denmark, Estonia, France, Greece, Hungary,
Italy, Latvia, the Netherlands, Portugal, Moldova, Romania,
Russia, Slovenia, Spain, Switzerland, the United Kingdom and the
United States of America.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, 43 delegations signed the final act of the
diplomatic conference for the adoption of the Geneva act. They are
Algeria, Argentina, Belgium, Bulgaria, Chad, China, Cote d"Ivoire,
Croatia, Cuba, the Czech Republic, Denmark, Ecuador, Estonia,
Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Hungary, Ireland, Italy, Japan,
Kenya, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, the Netherlands, Norway, Panama,
Portugal, Moldova, Romania, Russia, Slovakia, Slovenia, Spain,
Swaziland, Sweden, Switzerland, Turkey, Uganda, the United
Kingdom, the United States, and the European Community.
</P>
<P>
The new act, expected to enter into force after six
ratifications of over 80 contracting parties, introduces a number
of important changes to the Hague system for the registration of
industrial designs, according to WIPO.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva act enhances the existing system for the
international registration of industrial designs by making it more
compatible with the registration systems in countries such as the
United States and Japan where protection of industrial designs is
contingent on examination determine the acceptability of an
application.
</P>
<P>
One of the main advantages of using the Hague system is that it
allows users to include up to as many as 100 designs in each
international application that is made. In 1998, WIPO registered
about 4,000 international deposits each covering on average 11
countries. This represented a 40 percent increase on the number
deposited 10 years previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
