<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's 2nd Anti-Malaria Project to Cost $2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
regional office for Africa said here Tuesday that the second Roll
Back Malaria (RBM) project in Africa will cost two billion U.S.
dollars to implement over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a report released in Harare Tuesday that
there is an absolute shortage of funds for health on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The cost for the 2nd anti-malaria project was established by
the project partnership meeting held in Harare last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Roll Back Malaria project is a broad network of national
governments, international and bilateral organizations,
non-governmental organizations, the private sector and others
contributing resources and skills to reduce the malaria burden
across the globe.
</P>
<P>
It was launched in New York in October 1998 by the WHO, the
United Nations Children's Education Fund, the U.N. Development
Fund and the World Bank, but was formally established in Geneva
two months later.
</P>
<P>
The anti-malaria project partnership meeting in Harare stressed
the need for both short-term and long-term mobilization strategies
and for governments and donors to jointly develop flexible,
transparent funding mechanisms and reporting systems.
</P>
<P>
On the progress made in rolling back malaria in Africa, the
report said activities undertaken included the development of a
draft strategy, work plan, advocacy materials and a framework for
monitoring progress.
</P>
<P>
Programs set for implementation over the next two years include
the development of a framework for country-level implementation of
the Roll Back Malaria project, identification of country needs and
provision of appropriate resources and the institution of
functional partnerships at national and local levels in
malaria-endemic countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
