<HEADLINE> U.S., Britain Accused of Blocking Iraqi Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Tuesday accused the U.S. and
British envoys with the U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking the
approval of the contracts of its communications sector under the
oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Murtadha, Minister of Transport and Communications, told
the Iraqi News Agency that the Sanctions Committee is still
holding the contracts his ministry signed with foreign companies
eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not say how many contracts are on hold or how
much they are worth.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.N. had earlier allocated 150 million
U.S. dollars to meet the needs of the communications sector, but
later reduced the amount on the ground that it would affect other
basic needs of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Murtadha argued that services of his sector are needed by
the food distribution centers all over the country, as they are
needed by hospitals to treat patients.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991 Gulf War, most of Iraq's communications
systems were destroyed by the U.S.-led western allies.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food program, Iraq is allowed to export
limited amount of oil in every six months to buy food, medicine
and other humanitarian supplies for its nearly 24 million people
reeling under the U.N. sanctions imposed following its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant U.N. resolutions, all contracts signed by the
Iraqi government with foreign companies must get the approval of
the U.N. Sanctions Committee before shipment can be made.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long complained that U.S. and British envoys with
the Sanctions Committee deliberately impede the approval of its
contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
