<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges Rebuilding of Confidence in Peace Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
Tuesday called for efforts to rebuild confidence in the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the call when he was speaking to reporters after a
meeting between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat. Arafat left Cairo after the meeting, ending
a brief visit.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister lashed out at the outgoing
Israeli prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, for shattering the
confidence due to his hardline policy toward the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"The most important step to rebuild confidence is to implement
the agreements" signed between the Palestinians and Israel, Moussa
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The foremost of the agreements that should be honored is the
Wye accord of October 1998, he said, adding that the Israeli
settlement policy, confiscation and demolition of Palestinian
houses should be stopped.
</P>
<P>
Under the interim peace accord, Israel should withdraw from
another 13 percent of the West Bank. But the Netanyahu government
halted troop pullback in December. It also supported the building
of Jewish settlements on Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was defeated by moderate leader of the Israeli Labor
Party Ehud Barak in the country's May 17 elections. Barak's
victory has increased hopes for the revival of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's caution, however, was believed to be prompted by a
euphoria maintained by both Israeli and Arab peace activists.
</P>
<P>
Consultations among Arab parties concerned with the peace
process "are essential at this stage" to draw up a political line
that should be followed, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
"As a new government is about to be formed, it is important for
us to know what line that government will take regarding the peace
process," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
