<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean FM Optimistic at Draft Cease-fire Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan
Mudenge said in Lusaka Tuesday he hoped that the ministers would
finalize by the end of the day the draft cease-fire document to
end the war in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The minister said this in an interview with the Zimbabwe News
Agency Ziana before the relevant African ministers met for their
last plenary session Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The African ministers had by Saturday evening adopted the peace
accord to end the war, disclosed Mudenge.
</P>
<P>
However, Uganda and Rwanda were reportedly now introducing new
demands, which the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
allies have rejected.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda do not want the Organization of African Unity
and the United Nations to police the peace-keeping process, said
the Zimbabwean foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, accused of aiding the Congolese rebels alongside
Uganda, had wanted Zimbabwe to take responsibility of the Hutu
militia in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and disarm them.
</P>
<P>
The major players in the Congo (K) war saw it fit to have an
international peace-keeping force either from the U.N. or the OAU
to enforce any truce in the third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge said the talks would end Tuesday evening even if they
do not conclude the discussions.
</P>
<P>
"We are going for last minute private consultations. Within an
hour, we are going to report to the plenary session. It is at
this last session that we will know if we have agreed or not," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Even if we do not, we are all going back to our
individual countries and continue consulting."
</P>
<P>
The ministers from the 14 SADC countries, from Rwanda and
Uganda among others who had been meeting since June 26, were now
working on the time- table to implement the accord.
</P>
<P>
While the rebels are allegedly backed by Rwanda and Uganda,
Congolese President Laurent Kabila is enjoying military support
from Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
