<HEADLINE> Arafat: Palestinians Ready to Build Peace With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- President of the Palestinian National
Authority Yasser Arafat said Tuesday that the Palestinians were
ready to build peace together with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Arafat expressed the desire in response to the remarks by
Israeli Prime Minister-Elect Ehud Barak before the Knesset
(parliament) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to bravely go together towards peace under the
signed accords with late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin," he
said upon his return from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
After six weeks of coalition talks, Barak submitted the list of
his nineteen-minister cabinet to the Knesset Tuesday for approval.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Israeli lawmakers, Barak said he was ready to
push forward the peace process on the Palestinian, Syrian and
Lebanese tracks in a bid to reach peace with the Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks on all tracks have been stalled under the outgoing
hardline Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Arafat met Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and discussed with him the latest developments of the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader briefed Arafat on the results of his recent
tours of Washington and Paris. The two sides also reviewed some
issues of common concern, on top of which are the situation in the
Arab world and the bilateral ties. 
</P>
