<HEADLINE> Ghana's Anti-Drug Program Lauded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Drug Control Program
(UNDCP) has lauded Ghana's anti-drug program as worthy of
emulation in the sub-region, the Ghana News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Quantson, Executive Secretary of the Ghanaian Narcotics
Control Board, said in Accra tuesday that the UNDCP, which
supports the board with logistics and funds, singled out Ghana's
anti-drug laws and law enforcement structure as an example for
other west African countries to emulate.
</P>
<P>
Quantson told the press that the track record of his board has
improved upon the country's previously dented image in the early
1990s when Ghana was regarded as a major transit point for
narcotic drugs.
</P>
<P>
"The UNDCP is assisting in providing vehicles and other
technical equipment," said Quantson.
</P>
<P>
He said that the European Union, under its African Anti-Drug
Program, also plans to give a face-lift to the Department of
Social Welfare's Rehabilitation Center to treat drug-related
patients discharged from the Psychiatric Hospital, which is the
only facility currently handling such cases in this west African
country.
</P>
<P>
The anti-drug official said the best way to win the war against
drugs is for everyone to approach it with equal responsibility.
</P>
