<HEADLINE> Mideast Peace Talks to Be Resumed Soon: Peres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud
Barak will resume peace talks with all Arab neighbors soon, former
Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Barak is a man who keeps his promises, Peres told a conference
on peace in Cairo. "It will not take too long before we shall see
the renewal of the Mideast peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Peres, who discussed the stalled peace process with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak earlier Tuesday, was attending a meeting
of the International Alliance for Arab-Israeli Peace that was set
up in Denmark in 1997. The three-day conference is sponsored by
Denmark and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Barak's government, which is expected to take office late in
the day, "will move swiftly to the way of peace on all tracks and
to all other alternatives to bring peace to our region," Peres
said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's peace talks with Syria and Lebanon have been stalled
since early 1996, while the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations
failed to make significant progress during the outgoing government
of hard-line Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Barak trounced Netanyahu in Israel's May 17 elections. Barak
has promised to advance negotiations with the Palestinians and
Syria, and to withdraw Israeli forces from Lebanon in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
A former Israeli education minister and well-known left-winger,
Shulamit Aloni, was equally optimistic about the prospects for the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Trust the people of Israel, they voted for peace and they are
fed up with wars," Aloni, a former leader of the moderate Meretz
Party, told the conference.
</P>
<P>
But Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, who did not attend
the conference, urged caution on Tuesday. Moussa said what is
needed at present are steps to rebuild confidence in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting between Mubarak and
visiting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Moussa called for the
implementation of the agreements signed between the Palestinians
and Israel, the foremost of which is the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
He also urged an end to the construction of Jewish settlements,
the confiscation of Arab property and lands, and the demolition of
Arab houses.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government had halted its military withdrawals
from the West Bank under the Wye accord of October 1998, and had
supported the building of Jewish settlements on Palestinian land.
</P>
</TEXT>
