<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Efforts to Release Missing Iranians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Tuesday called for continuation of the international
efforts for the release of the four Iranians who have missed for
17 years.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the appeal in his letters to the United Nations
Secretary General, head of the International Committee of the Red
Cross, rotating president of the European Union, Lebanese prime
minister and Syrian foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He held Israel responsible for the fate of the Iranian
diplomats, who Iran believed to have been abducted by Israel from
Lebanon in 1982, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Zionist (Israeli) regime tries to forget the abduction
case," Kharrazi said, but evidences proved that the Iranian
diplomats are still alive and were transferred to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry Sunday also urged Israel to release
the missing Iranians and said that Israel should directly bear the
responsibility for the missing of the Iranians with the
consideration of evidences.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the Lebanese government to use all
possibilities to probe into the case and seek the release of the
Iranian diplomats and also urged international human rights
groups to help clarify the fate of the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Israel entered a new round of tension following the
arrest of 13 Iranian Jews on charge of spying for Israel and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Both Israel and the U.S. have rejected the Iranian claims and
called on Tehran to release the Iranians immediately.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran has stated that the Iranian Jews would be tried
according to Iranian laws and they might be sentenced to death for
spying against the country's security.  
</P>
</TEXT>
