<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Should Have One Voice in Debt Negotiation: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Africa should have one voice in
negotiating relief on its 233 billion U.S. dollars foreign debt,
Spokesman of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) Ibrahim
Dagash said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the remarks here when briefing journalists
on the ongoing African ambassadors' meeting.
</P>
<P>
The massive debt was pulling down Africa's development efforts
because needed resources were diverted to repay borrowed funds.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is the servicing of the debt which is killing
Africa," he said, adding that the OAU's objective was to talk to
Africa's creditors with one voice instead of waiting for the
creditors to approach individual debt-ridden states separately.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he noted, the OAU has set up a five-member
contact group from Africa's five regions to spearhead the debt
relief talks with the creditors.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures released by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), more than half of African countries
are suffering from their external debt, which has undermined the
development of their respective economies.
</P>
<P>
The staggering external debt of African countries has hindered
the revitalization of Africa's relatively small and weak
economies.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three of a total of the world's 48 poorest countries are
in Africa and nearly half of the African population are living
under the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid growth of economies elsewhere, African economies
have been further marginalized in the global arena.
</P>
<P>
Africa's trade now accounts for only 1.2 percent of the world's
total, down from 3.1 percent 30 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghanaian VP Calls for Wider Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian Vice-President John Evans
Atta Mills Tuesday called for a wider social security coverage in
the African continent, the Ghana News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 13th International Social Security Association
Africa Regional Conference in Accra, the vice-president said that
the time has come for Africa to rid its social security schemes of
dogmas that might have served a passing age.
</P>
<P>
Social security schemes in Africa cover below 30 percent of the
 working population as compared to 100 percent in the developed
world.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president told over 200 representatives from Africa
and personnel from the International Social Security Association
as well as other related world bodies that social security schemes
in Africa need to be re-engineered to be in tune with the
socio-cultural realities of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mills said as the continent moves toward the new millennium
with hope, progress and security for its people, social protection
must be based on comprehensive and sustainable social security
programs.
</P>
<P>
Only a small fraction, mostly urbanized workers in most African
 countries, has been registered under social security schemes.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president challenged this conference to come out with
an Accra Declaration on social security for the 21st century
"which will address the fundamental needs we have identified."
</P>
<P>
Most existing social security schemes in Africa took off after
 independence to benefit government employees and others in the
formal sector.
</P>
<P>
The schemes operated on the selected needs of a minority of
workers without taking into account the wider social protection
needs of the entire population.
</P>
<P>
The conference, under a broad theme of "Social Security in
Africa: New Realities," will be an attempt to make the scheme
more appealing to the wider segment of the population not covered.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
