<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Peace Talks on Verge of Collapse: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks aimed at ending the
11-month conflict in Congo (K) fell in deadlock Tuesday after
Rwanda said it would not back down on a demand that exiled Hutu
militia be disarmed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials attending the meeting here said that the talks,
which have been dragging on for close to two weeks in Zambian
capital Lusaka, were now on the verge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
They are accusing Rwanda, Uganda and Zimbabwe of delaying the
signing of a cease-fire agreement. The three countries have sent
their troops fighting in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
One of the officials who declined to be named said that the
last minute demands by Rwanda and Uganda are delaying the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
He said the talks are deadlocked over the Interahamwe Hutu
militias. The key issue is who disarms them and how this should be
done.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda want Zimbabwe to take responsibility for the
militia but Zimbabwe dismissed, said the official.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe told a consultative meeting of belligerents
that it did not have the resistances to carry out the operations
demanded by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Zimbabwe said the task of disarming the Interahamwe be
lift to the United Nations as agreed upon in the primary session
at the beginning of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Another official said unless the issue of the militia is
resolved, the Lusaka talks are bound to collapse, noting that the
Rwandans are not budging and neither are the Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the belligerent parties are also
grappling over the issue of the deployment of a United Nations
peace-keeping force in the DRC with Uganda and Rwanda insisting on
a joint military council to oversee the implementation of a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The issue would be tabled at the ministers' plenary session
expected to resume later for consideration, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace talks have been held under the guidance of
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, who was mandated by the U.N.,
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) to seek peace in the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
