<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Population Stabilization Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Tuesday that human beings should be responsible for
the well-being of their children.
</P>
<P>
In his message on the occasion of World Population Day which
falls on July 11, Annan said parents should ensure that their
children will have a life of dignity.
</P>
<P>
The global community should use natural resources more wisely
and share them more equitably, said the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
For the Earth to continue to sustain all in the future, the
world population must be stabilized, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we remain committed, continue to cooperate and give the
right message to the young people of today, who will shape
tomorrow's world population, we will contribute to a better future
for all," he said.
</P>
<P>
World Population Day was first celebrated on July 11, 1989 to
focus attention on the urgency and importance of population
issues particularly in the context of overall development plans and
programs and the need to find solutions to the issues.
</P>
<P>
This year world population will pass 6 billion and the World
Population Day follows a U.N. General Assembly special session to
review and appraise the implementation of the 20-year Program of
Action on population and development adopted at the Cairo
Conference in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The June 30-July 2 special session adopted key actions for the
further implementation of the document.
</P>
<P>
They include efforts by governments to integrate population
concerns into national development strategies, to reduce poverty,
provide education to all, reduce maternal mortality and promote
reproductive health including family planning.
</P>
<P>
The special session urged donors to be more generous in
reacting to developing countries' needs to meet population
challenges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Coalition Parties in New Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The government of Prime Minister
Ehud Barak took office Tuesday after the Knesset (parliament)
approved the seven-faction coalition, which controls 75 seats in
the 120-member.
</P>
<P>
Barak-led One Israel, consisting of the Labor Party, Gesher of
Middle East Jews and the moderate religious party Meimad, gained
26 seats, becoming the largest party in the Knesset. The alliance
supports comprehensive peace with Arab neighbors and free-market
economy with attention to social welfare.
</P>
<P>
The ultra-Orthodox Shas party of the Middle East Jews, whose
convicted leader Aryeh Deri resigned soon after the election to
clear way for the party's entrance into the coalition.
</P>
<P>
It is the third largest party with 17 seats. The Shas focuses
on religious affairs, moderate on the peace process, and its
support is seen as vital for Barak's peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing Meretz Zionist party led by Education Minister
Yossi Sarid garnered 10 seats. Considered as a natural ruling
partner in Labor-led governments, it supports peace with Arab
neighbors and an independent Palestinian state. Domestically, it
stands for the separation of religion and state.
</P>
<P>
The Russian immigrants party Yisrael b'Aliya, winning six seats
and led by Interior Minister Natan Sharansky has been seeking
welfare for Russian immigrants and is considered as moderate right
on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The ultra-Orthodox party of European Jews United Torah Judaism,
having five seats, is primarily concerned with religious issues
and striving for blocking the drafting of religious students. It
supports the coalition but does not sit in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
National Religious Party, with five seats, is a religious
Zionist party with roots going back to the early days of
Zionism. Since the mid-70s it has shifted to the right, advocating
the Greater Land of Israel and Jewish settlements in occupied
Palestinian territory. Led by Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy, it is
the only right-wing party in Barak's government.
</P>
<P>
Center Party, with six seats, is a party of defectors from the
right-wing Likud and other parties, and formed before the May
election. Led by Transportation Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, it
supports the continuation of peace process and calls for the
unity of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
