<HEADLINE> Turkish President Praises Romanian Efforts Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
Tuesday expressed satisfaction over Romanian efforts to put an
end to the presence of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Demirel thanked Romanian President Emil Constantinescu, who
arrived here on Tuesday for a two-day official visit, for
Romanian cooperation in Turkey's struggle against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Romania has always supported Turkey in the struggle against
terrorism and organized crime. The Romanian security forces
operation against groups affiliated with the PKK on April 27,
1999, is the concrete proof of Romania's efforts," added Demirel.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Turkey, Romania and Bulgaria signed a trilateral
agreement on a joint struggle against terrorism and organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
Romanian authorities have recently intensified efforts to crack
down on the PKK and its affiliates in Romania, and have extradited
a number of PKK members to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Demirel also expressed his desire for accelarated economic
ties between Turkey and Romania.
</P>
<P>
"Romania is Turkey's biggest trade partner in the Balkans and
the Middle East. Turkey is the biggest foreign investor in
Romania with some 1.2 billion U.S. dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president pointed out that "our bilateral trade
volume has reached 813 million U.S. dollars last year and it is
expected to exceed 1 billion dollars in a short period of time."
</P>
<P>
Following the talks between Demirel and Constantinescus, the
two sides signed a consular agreement and a protocol on
cooperation in social security.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the two presidents are scheduled to address
a meeting of the Turco-Romanian Business Council in Istanbul,
the largest city of Turkey. 
</P>
