<HEADLINE> Turkish Deputy PM Blasts EU Stance on PKK Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Deputy Prime Minister
Develet Bahceli Tuesday harshly criticized the European Union
(EU)'s position on the death sentence on the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) leader Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to his Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) in the
parliament, Bahceli also called on the EU to revise its policies
towards Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Western European countries, which are against the death
penalty, called on Turkey not to hang Ocalan after he was
sentenced to death last Tuesday on charges of treason and
separatism.
</P>
<P>
Bahceli said that "the hullabaloo created for the pardon of
the terrorist chieftain has displayed once again the EU's
hypocritical attitude on terrorism and towards Turkey."
</P>
<P>
He said that "our party believes that the EU must revise its
policies on Turkey and launch a process of self-criticism."
</P>
<P>
Bahceli lashed out at the EU for not taking adequate measures
to prevent PKK attacks on Turkish establishments in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He also singled out Italy and Greece as the spokesmen and
advocates of the PKK and accused them of having played an
important part in its development.
</P>
<P>
The Ocalan-led PKK has been fighting a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey since 1984. Conflicts between
the Turkish security forces and the PKK militants have claimed
over 37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was captured by Turkish special agents in Kenya in
mid-February and has ever since been detained on Imrali Island
in Marmara Sea near western Turkey's province of Bursa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
