<HEADLINE> Security Urged in East Timor Ahead of Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday called on Indonesia to maintain peace and security in East
Timor as a ballot to determine the territory's future is
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Council deplored the attack by armed militias on
a U.N. Mission convoy delivering humanitarian assistance on July
4, Council President Malaysia's Agam Hasmy told the press
following closed consultations.
</P>
<P>
The Council heard a briefing by U.N. Assistant
Secretary-General De Soto on the situation in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Agam said the Council demanded an immediate halt to the
practice of violence and intimidation by the militias.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council called upon the Indonesian authorities
to investigate the matter and to bring to justice those
responsible for the recent attacks on the U.N. Mission in East
Timor (UNAMET)," the presidential statement said.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMET was created by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
organize and conduct the so-called popular consultation in East
Timor to see whether the majority of the 800,000 East Timorese
would choose special autonomy within Indonesia or independence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a Portuguese colony until 1975, was occupied by
Indonesia in the same year and annexed in 1976. Under the auspices
of the U.N. which calls it a non-self-governing territory,
Indonesia and Portugal reached an agreement on May 5 for a vote in
August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
