<HEADLINE> Angola Urged to Release Russian Pilots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Embassy in Luanda said
Tuesday that the Russian government has called upon the Angolan
rebel movement UNITA to release the Russian crew members of the
two planes downed in northeastern Angola.
</P>
<P>
The embassy said in a press release that the Russian Foreign
Ministry issued a statement in Moscow Tuesday demanding that the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), and its
leader Jonas Savimbi in particular, to take necessary steps to
enable the pilots to return home.
</P>
<P>
The press release again denied that the Russian pilots were
involved in military operation in the war-ravaged southern African
country, claiming that they were just doing civilian transport.
</P>
<P>
An Antonov-26 and an Antonov-12 were shot down in Lunda-Norte
Province on May 12 and June 30 this year respectively. The
Russian pilots on the planes were detained by the UNITA troops.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA said in Portuguese capital Lisbon last Friday that
its troops captured four Russian pilots in Xa-Muteba city, 500 kms
west of Luanda. Another Russian pilot had died of serious burns
after the Antonov-12 crashed.
</P>
<P>
Three Russian pilots survived the May 12 crash, and they had
been taken to Andulo city, the UNITA's headquarters in the central
highlands.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group claimed that these Russian pilots had been
mercenaries fighting for the Angolan government army, saying that
they would be punished for what they had done.
</P>
<P>
However, both the Angolan government and the Russian government
have said again and again that these pilots were employed by the
local companies to transport food and mining machinery to the
northeastern part of the war-torn country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
