<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Picks Up In May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- British industrial production was
stronger than expected in May, suggesting that the long decline in
manufacturing may be at an end.
</P>
<P>
The upturn was taken as a sign that the UK economy is on track
for solid growth in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics monthly manufacturing
production figure rose 0.3 percent compared to April although it
was still down 0.8 percent on May last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures for the latest three months showed manufacturing
output, which accounts for about a fifth of the country's economic
activity, rose 0.5 percent from the previous three months -- the
strongest performance for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
Signs that manufacturing may at last have turned the corner
suggest the government may be on target with its prediction of 1
percent economic growth this year after a flat first quarter of
1999.
</P>
<P>
Neil Parker, Royal Bank of Scotland economist, said, "The data
is very encouraging with regard to the prospects for the UK
economy going forward." 
</P>
</TEXT>
