<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Launches Health Drive to Save Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- UK Health Secretary Frank Dobson
Tuesday announced ambitious targets to save 300,000 lives over the
next 10 years by cutting deaths from cancer, heart disease,
accidents and suicide.
</P>
<P>
Launching a White Paper on public health in England, Dobson
said the government also aimed to reduce the health inequalities
between the rich and the poor. He accused the previous
Conservative government of exacerbating the problems with their
policies.
</P>
<P>
"We want to help make sure that the standard of health of the
people they (the Tories) represent in Surrey or Sutton Coldfield
is shared by the people we represent in Barnsley or Bethnal
Green," he said. "We want to end the divisions that mar our
society."
</P>
<P>
Dobson outlined four specific targets contained in the paper,
including the reduction of deaths from cancer among people under
75 by at least a fifth, deaths from coronary heart disease among
people under 75 by at least two-fifths, deaths by accidents by at
least a fifth and serious injury by at least a tenth, and suicides
by at least a fifth.
</P>
<P>
The targets, to be achieved by 2010, would be "backed by
action," he said, adding that "we will see a healthier nation as a
result of this White Paper."
</P>
<P>
There would be specific action to improve people's diet, and to
cut smoking, the biggest single preventable cause of death in the
UK. Also, the role of health visitors, community and school nurses
and midwives would be extended, according to the health secretary.
</P>
<P>
A Health Skills program will be launched to teach first aid
skills and health information to young people, and an Expert
Patients scheme will enable people with chronic conditions such as
asthma and diabetes to more effectively manage their own
conditions, according to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Hold over 18 Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices held above 18 U.S.
dollars a barrel on Tuesday despite shedding some early gains as
markets drew support from fresh evidence that OPEC tightened
supply in June.
</P>
<P>
World marker Brent blend crude for August delivery ended seven
cents lower at 18.11 U.S. dollars per barrel. The London market
had opened stronger but failed to hold the morning's gains as some
profit-taking kicked in.
</P>
<P>
IPE Brent jumped 51 cents on Monday to trade at its highest in
18 months, climbing into the bottom end of OPEC's target price
range between 18 and 20 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
OPEC producers, buoyed by a rally that has added 8 U.S. dollars
a barrel to the price from February's historic lows, improved
adherence with bespoke output cuts in place since April.
</P>
<P>
A Reuters survey of production by members of the Organisation
of the Petroleum Exporting Countries, excluding Iraq, showed a
compliance level of 89 percent in June, from 85 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
OPEC reduced output in June by 290,000 barrels a day (bpd) to
25.85 million, according to a survey of OPEC and industry
officials, analysts and consultants.
</P>
<P>
"OPEC is holding the line on production," Reuters quoted
Washington consultancy Petroleum Finance as saying, adding that
OPEC was on course to wipe out surplus inventories by the end of
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
U.S. weekly oil stocks data, an important market indicator due
to be published on Wednesday, will provide further insight into
whether the supply curbs are helping to erode the oil stockpile in
the world's largest economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
