<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers Aid for Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Clinton is
offering a mix of public and private investment to spur economic
activity in some of the nation's poor communities, as he began his
four-day tour through the U.S. inner cities and rural areas from
Appalachia to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
"I want everybody in America to know that while our country has
been blessed with this economic recovery, not all Americans have
been blessed by it," Clinton told about 600 people gathered in a
tin-roofed warehouse in Clarksdale. He noted the poverty and
unemployment rates in the Mississippi Delta region far exceed the
national averages.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was announcing 64 million dollars in community
development grants Tuesday, including 15 million dollars for the
Delta region, before joining a Bank of America executive in East
St. Louis, to outline a new 500 million dollars capital investment
fund.
</P>
<P>
During the tour, a handful of corporate leaders are
accompanying President Clinton and several Cabinet secretaries and
politicians as they review local projects and deliver promises of
investment and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
The president announced 60 million dollars in grants from the
Community Development Financial Institutions Fund to community
development organizations across the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cathy Bessant, a vice president of Bank of America,
committed 100 million dollars to the fund. Later in the day, with
Clinton by her side, she announced formation of a 500 million
capital investment fund targeted at often-overlooked communities.
</P>
<P>
"There is real money to be made in these markets," Bressant
said. "We think we can be even more successful when we create
markets that work in inner cities." 
</P>
</TEXT>
