<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miraculous Escape for Cliff Plunge Driver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- British coastguards say a teenager
is lucky to be alive after a miraculous escape when her car
plunged up to 200 ft down a cliff.
</P>
<P>
Three-quarters of the way down the 18-year-old was thrown from
the car and wedged by her right leg and hip between two rocks. She
was unconscious for about three hours, but when she came round,
she was able to call for help using her mobile phone.
</P>
<P>
Ambulance control staff had to ring the woman back, who was
disorientated and crying, six times because her phone kept cutting
out, according to the police.
</P>
<P>
Eventually the woman, named as Rebecca Richards from Torpoint,
Cornwall, the UK, was able to establish that she was in the area
of Whitsand Bay, near Freathy, in south-east Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers then searched the area for 45 minutes before a Sea
King helicopter from RNAS Culdrose found her.
</P>
<P>
The driver was wedged between rocks after being thrown clear of
the car. A paramedic and an ambulance technician climbed up the
cliff to reach her from the beach below and fitted an intravenous
drip.
</P>
<P>
She was taken to Roborough Airport and from there to Derriford
Hospital in Plymouth with injuries to her right leg, neck and
face. She was also suffering from clinical shock and hypothermia,
but her injuries were not thought to be life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
Her car, a blue Vauxhall Nova, was found badly damaged on the
beach below.
</P>
<P>
Steve Twaits, watch manager at Brixham Coastguard, said, "It is
quite extraordinary that the woman was conscious after such a fall
and was able to dial 999 from her mobile phone." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
