<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drumcree Parade Banned Again in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Northern Ireland Parades
Commission on Tuesday again refused to allow Portadown Orange
Lodge to march along the mainly nationalist Garvaghy Road on
Sunday, 11 July.
</P>
<P>
The lodge has been applying to parade on the road every Sunday
since last year's controversial Drumcree march was re-routed.
</P>
<P>
But Portadown Orangemen spokesman David Jones said he is
confident the parade will eventually take place.
</P>
<P>
"It must be borne in mind, this time last year, we had just
arrived on the hill," BBC quoted him as saying. "However, this
year we have already been out on the hill for 12 months so really
we are on day 367 and I think now they have got to realize that
the parade may go down in the future."
</P>
<P>
The Orange Order remains in touch with British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, but as yet has received no definite indication that
Portadown District will be allowed to parade.
</P>
<P>
Orangemen are still maintaining a protest at Drumcree following
a Parades Commission decision to ban them from marching down the
Garvaghy Road on 4 July.
</P>
<P>
Minor scuffles erupted on Monday night between loyalists and
the security forces with six policemen being injured. Two people
were arrested and a heavy security presence remains. However, the
Orange Order has said it remains happy about the way the protest
is being conducted.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday the commission issued determinations covering a
number of parades over the busiest period of the marching calendar
10-15 July. The vast majority of hundreds of parades will take
place exactly as notified by the organisers, but a few have had
conditions imposed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Praises Peru for Maintaining Macroeconomic Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Tuesday commended the authorities of Peru for their efforts
to maintain macroeconomic stability and pursue reforms in the face
of the deteriorating external environment.
</P>
<P>
"Executive directors welcomed the authorities' overall strong
record of prudent economic management throughout this decade,
which had been reflected in the impressive strides made toward the
creation of conditions for sustained noninflationary growth and
current account viability, as well as progress in poverty
alleviation," the IMF said in its annual review of the Peruvian
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, over the last 12 to 18 months, a number of external
shocks, including the EI Nino weather phenomenon, had adversely
affected the country's economic performance. As a result, the real
gross domestic product (GDP) growth slowed to 0.7 percent in 1998,
and the fiscal position shifted from balance to a deficit of 0.5
percent of GDP as weak economic activity restrained tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
The government's economic program for 1999 assumes a 3 percent
growth in real GDP and envisages inflation during the year of 6
percent, a decline in the external current account deficit, and a
moderate accumulation of net international reserves that would
keep gross international reserves in the range of 11-12 months of
imports of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The IMF welcomed the authorities's intention to give emphasis
to the government's structural reform agenda.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that the flexible exchange rate system had helped
the economy adjust to external shocks, and supported the
authorities' intention to continue with such a system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
