<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Says Kosovars Continue Returning Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 600,000 Kosovar
refugees have returned home, according to a report by United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About 16,700 refugees headed home Monday from neighboring
Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro, the organization said.
</P>
<P>
With the returns, the estimated number of Kosovo Albanian
refugees and displaced people in the region has dropped to
150,100, including 22,200 in Montenegro, 19,000 in Macedonia,
91,500 in Albania and 17,400 in Bosnia-Herzegovina, it was
updated.
</P>
<P>
Organized returns form Montenegro are expected to start
Wednesday and arrangements are being made to start the first
voluntary repatriation from Europe and other areas to which
Kosovars were evacuated during 78 days of NATO airstrikes against
Yugoslavia since March 24.  
</P>
</TEXT>
