<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Aims for "Enterprise Culture" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Tuesday unveiled a 50m pounds fund to back budding
entrepreneurs, saying that "years of snobbery" in the UK against
those seeking to make money had to end if the economy was to
thrive in the future.
</P>
<P>
Both the Tory elite and the traditional Labour Party "showed a
certain snobbery towards people who had an idea, developed it and
went out and made money," Blair said. "Too often in Britain, if
people saw someone with money, they were jealous of them, whereas
in the US they wanted to emulate them."
</P>
<P>
"The left regarded them as anti-social. When we should have
been hugely proud of our successful entrepreneurs, we tended
simply to wait until they fell flat on their faces and if possible
helped them do it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I want this government to be the champion of entrepreneurs,"
he said. "We need society as a whole to applaud you - you are the
front-line troops of Britain's new economy."
</P>
<P>
The 50m pounds funding would be spread among the regional
development agencies. Proposals are being invited for the design
and running of the funds which would invest money in businesses -
providing what is known as venture capital, according to a BBC
report.
</P>
<P>
By bringing in public finance, the aim is to encourage private
individuals or firms to invest some of their venture capital funds
in the sort of small, high-risk firms which they might otherwise
shun.
</P>
<P>
Blair said the fund had to build on, rather than duplicate,
existing sources of funding from banks and existing venture
capital funds.
</P>
<P>
In the speech to the British Venture Capital Association
conference in London, Blair promised that the next Budget would
include "new incentives for corporate venturing".
</P>
<P>
Also, he urged pension funds "to examine whether they and other
institutional investors are being too cautious when it comes to
venture capital and investing in early-stage companies". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
