<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Middle East Peace Train Ready to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- After three years of delay and
derailment, the Middle east peace process was ready to restart in
full gear Tuesday after Israeli new Prime Minister Ehud Barak
officially assumed office.
</P>
<P>
As expected, the Israeli Knesset (Parliament) voted 75-29,
with 11 abstention, to approve the Barak's government, which
controls 75 seats in the 120-member house. The 18 cabinet
ministers from the seven coalition parties were sworn in after
the parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
While presenting his cabinet to the Knesset, Barak pledged to
work for a comprehensive peace with all Arab neighbors of Israel
and to give same priorities to peace process on the Palestinian
and the Syrian tracks.
</P>
<P>
One of the most-decorated soldiers in Israel, Barak began his
speech by citing his 35 years of military career to explain his
motivation to make peace.
</P>
<P>
"I called on all regional leaders to take our outstretched
hand and to make a peace of the brave in the area," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent bid to ease fears of the Palestinians and
Syrians that they might be played against each other while he
resumed the stalled peace talks, the ex-army chief said peace with
Syria and the Palestinians are "equally vital" to Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The reaching of a permanent agreement with the Palestinians
and the achieving of peace with Syria and Lebanon are equally
vital and urgent in my eyes," he said.
</P>
<P>
After winning the May election, Barak and Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad have heaped praise on each other and exchanged
messages of readiness through indirect channels to resume the
peace talks, which was frozen three years ago.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Barak said his government was determined to
advance negotiations with Syria quickly.
</P>
<P>
"The new government of Israel is determined to advance
negotiations as quickly as possible to achieve a full bilateral
agreement on peace and security based on (U.N.) Security Council
resolutions 242 and 338," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolutions called on Israel to withdraw from Arab
territories Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East war, including
the Golan Heights of Syria.
</P>
<P>
Israel never entered official negotiations with Syria during
the three years of government of former hard-line prime minister
Benjamin Netanyau because he opposes territorial concession over
the Golan.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, who have expressed concern that Barak might
give priority to the Syrian talks and thus leave them behind, got
relieved when Barak said he would "give no priority" to any of
the two tracks.
</P>
<P>
"I want to work with the elected Palestinian leadership headed
by Yasser Arafat in a friendship and partnership in order to
achieve a proper co-existence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat welcomed Barak's remarks in Gaza, saying he is ready to
work with Barak to achieve the "peace of the brave."
</P>
<P>
Observers said the goodwill of the Israeli and the Arab sides,
together with the fact that Barak will conduct talks
simultaneously with the Palestinians and the Syrians, will help
the peace process move quickly.
</P>
<P>
By setting a one-year time frame for an Israeli withdrawal from
south Lebanon, he actually set a timetable for the Israeli-Syrian
talks because no agreement could be reached without including a
deal with Damascus, the main power-broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and the Syrians might actually compete in the
running in order not to be left behind, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which is enthusiastic over the victory of
the moderate Barak, has promised to do everything it can to help
move forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Barak talked with U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday night on
the phone and said Tuesday that he will visit Washington soon,
calling U.S. mediation role "vital" for the peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
This atmosphere, together with the fact that Barak has secured
one of the widest parliamentary majority in Israel in years, will
add fuel to the peace train.
</P>
<P>
Waiting anxiously for almost 50 days since Barak's election
victory, the Arab nations, as well as the international
community, are waiting to see the peace train start toward
bringing the Middle East into a peaceful 2lst century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Leone Peace Process, Finally at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Five African presidents and still
more high- ranking officials Tuesday gathered and may stay up far
into the night in Togolese capital Lome to try to give the
marathon styled Sierra Leone peace process a finial push.
</P>
<P>
Among the presidents to attend the mini-summit on Sierra Leone
peace are Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, Burkinabe
President Blaise Compaore, Liberian President Charles Taylor,
Sierra Leonean President Tejan Kabbah and their host Togolese
President Gnassingbe Eyadema.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Sierra Leone rebel leader Foday Sankoh, who has
already been in Lome for quite a long time for the peace talks,
one of the top commanders of the rebel troops also flew in Tuesday
to participate in the summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit was called upon by Eyadema, Togolese President and
current Chairman of the Economic Community of the West Africa
States (ECOWAS), at a critical moment of the Sierra Leone peace
Process.
</P>
<P>
After six week's negotiations, both sides have reached
agreement upon the framework of a peace plan, but remain
considerably different over many sticky points, which, if left
unresolved, might still ruin what has been hardly earned.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough appeared in the talks last week when the
Sierra Leonean government accepted, though reluctantly, the
power-sharing demand of the rebels and offered four ministerial
posts in a four-year transitional government to them.
</P>
<P>
Though rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) leader Sankoh
expressed his satisfaction at the first place, the People's War
Council, an organization of the rebels' field commanders rejected
the offer by demanding at least seven cabinet posts and a
vice-president position.
</P>
<P>
The rebels also made clear recently they are opposed to the
continued presence in Sierra Leone of the Nigeria-led ECOMOG
force, which has been fighting the rebels alongside the Kabbah
government.
</P>
<P>
The rebels also have doubts over the government's pledged
amnesty plan.
</P>
<P>
Recently many international human rights groups vehemently
accused them of systematically killing thousands of people, raping
and mutilating many others in the their decade-long war to gain
power.
</P>
<P>
These accusations have deepened the rebels' fears.
</P>
<P>
The mini-summit is geared to clear the hurdle, said Togolese
Foreign Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh, an active broker in the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Asked if a peace pact could be signed at the summit, Koffigoh
said: "If things progress well, it's possible."
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean President Kabbah also expressed high hopes for
peace on the eve of his departure for Lome, though in an address
to the nation late Monday he admitted the talks with the rebels
had made him unpopular with some Sierra Leoneans.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure many of you believe that the government has given
the RUF far too much already and the RUF has given very little or
nothing at all," Kabbah said.
</P>
<P>
But he added: "I have no doubt you will agree with me after so
much pain and sufferings, after so much destruction of life and
property, we need to exercise patience and persevere in our search
for a lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
The RUF has fought successive governments in Sierra Leone since
1991. The rebels almost took capital Freetown in a devastating
attack in January, which was finally defeated by the west African
peace-keeping force ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The chances of a deal in Lome have been boosted by the expected
presence of Liberian President Taylor and Burkinabe President
Compaore, both of whom have been accused in the region of backing
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
They deny any official assistance to the rebels but Taylor, a
former warlord in Liberia's seven-year conflict that ended in
1997, acknowledges past friendship with the RUF leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libya Demands Lifting of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Libya Tuesday demanded the
United Nations lift its seven-year sanctions against the north
African nation, saying that it had surrendered the two Libyans
accused of the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am airliner over the Scottish
town of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
"The politicalization of this legal dispute, in whatever form
or by anyone, is not acceptable," Libyan permanent representative
to the United Nations Abuzed Omar Dorda said in his nine-page
letter to the 15-nation Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The letter came as the Security Council is to meet on a Friday
report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who said that Libya
had complied with many demands set in the Security Council
resolution, but he was unable to make a recommendation on lifting
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Dorda said Libya's assurance, taken in connection
with the handover and his country's renunciation of terrorism were
enough to justify the permanent lifting measures now.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his report, said that Libya had pledged many times to
cooperate with the trial and pay compensation if the two suspects
were convicted, but acknowledged that he couldn't report on
Libya's actual compliance on those points because the trial had
not taken place.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. chief said that the United States needed more
evidence before it would agree to lift the sanctions, mainly
because the trial of the two suspects would not kick off before
February 2000.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, which include an air and arms embargo and a ban
on some oil equipment, were suspended on April 5, when Tripoli
surrendered for trial before a Scottish court in the Netherlands
the two Libyan suspects, who were accused of the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie. A total of 270 people were killed in
the explosion, and 189 of them were Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
