<HEADLINE> Council Backs Annan's Peace Efforts In Guinea-Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday endorsed the decision of Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
set up the U.N. Peace-Building Support Office in Guinea-Bissau
(UNOGBIS).
</P>
<P>
After hearing a briefing by U.N. Assistant Secretary-General De
Soto on the developments in the country, Council president
Malaysia's Agam Hasmy said Council members also urged the
transitional authorities and civil society in the country to
uphold their commitment.
</P>
<P>
The relevant parties have been committed to restoration of
genuine and lasting peace based on national reconciliation,
respect for the rule of law including the release of political
prisoners and the return to constitutional order.
</P>
<P>
Elections have been scheduled for November 28 this year.
</P>
<P>
Council members encouraged the government and other parties to
adopt a program of voluntary arms collection, disposal and
destruction, Agam told the press.
</P>
<P>
They also welcomed the U.N. chief's decision to establish a
Trust Fund in support of the activities of the UNOGBIS and
encouraged member states to contribute to the Fund, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the recommendations for the U.N.'s role in the
country in his latest report to the Council on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Despite President Vierira's ouster on May 7, Guinea-Bissau is
seeking to restore internal harmony and to improve relations with
the international community in particular with its neighbors, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
