<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR to Intensify Demining Work in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) will intensify demining work in Kosovo
beginning this week, the UNHCR office here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some experts who had experience in Cambodia and Mozambique,
including 30 Cambodians, are joining the teams that will fan out
in Kosovo as activities expand.
</P>
<P>
Priority areas include Pristina, Urosevac, Prizren, Suva Reka,
Djakovica, Pec, Podujevo, Gnjilane and Glogovac.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodians will head for Pec, a team of 30 Norwegian
experts will be sent to cover Prizen and Suva Reka, while Handicap
International is fielding two dog teams in Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
Seven clearance teams of Germany have been in Pristina,
Urosevac and Gnjilane, while other teams are preparing to move
out, depending on the results of the assessment survey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mine action program will be undertaken in three
phrases in support of the UNHCR's repatriation plan, which started
under a precondition that refugees are safe when they arrive in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In the first phrase, called Preliminary Phase, key activities
include mine awareness training for refugees, a rapid assessment
of the mine threat, and the establishment of mine actions
coordination centers.
</P>
<P>
In the second phrase, called Emergency Phases, key activities
include verification and survey, mine clearance of houses and key
installations.
</P>
<P>
The third phrase is Consolidation Phase with key activities
focusing on re-evaluating objectives and activities.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR Monday said that 40 incidents involving landmines or
explosives had taken place last week when refugees traveled back
to Kosovo, causing some people wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
