<HEADLINE> U.S. Threatens Russia Over Possible Arms Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States Tuesday
threatened Russia with suspension of American aid if Moscow should
sell more weapons to Syria.
</P>
<P>
The State Department made the point publicly as Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad visited Moscow for the first time since
the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Assad was seeking to renew ties with Russia and
acquire new weapons for Syria's defense.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of arms sales... we would be very concerned about any
new Russian arms sales to Syria," State Department deputy
spokesman James Foley said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that under U.S. law, Washington would stop any
assistance to Russia for its sale of weapons to Syria.
</P>
<P>
Despite the warning, Foley said Assad's visit could be a
"positive" event "if the aim is to try to build momentum for the
Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
The United States last April slapped sanctions on three Russian
companies for supplying anti-tank weapons to Syria.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials have argued that they consider Syria to be
the same as any other country and thus have a right to sell arms
to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
