<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Gains Little Foreign Investment For Lack of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The lack of a modern, well-trained
workforce is the primary reason Italy lags behind other European
nations in attracting foreign investments, according to an Italian
Senate study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign companies, Italy must open up its business
practices, liberalize its markets, but most of all, modernize its
workforce, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Leonardo Caponi, president of the Italian Senate's Industry
Committee, focused on the findings of the study, said Tuesday that
the high cost of labor is a problem, but "decisively more
important is the quality of the work force and the offer of
services for training and qualification."
</P>
<P>
Italian Industry Minister Pierluigi Bersani said that 1,600
branches of multi-national companies employing 500,000 Italians,
have produced 210 trillion lire (116 billion U.S. dollars) of
output, but added that Italy still lags behind Europe in
attracting foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
"We are behind in this field for the same reason we are behind
in the process of internationalization of our own companies,"
Bersani said.
</P>
<P>
"It's necessary to move ahead the process of liberalization and
privatization both to attract foreign capital and to see our
system of business grow," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
