<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Clean Sweep Women's Gymnastic Titles at Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Russian women gymnasts
headed by Olympic champion Svetlana Khorkina, made a clean sweep
of six gold medals at stake the gymnastic competitions concluded
at the 20th World University Games here Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Khorkina, the all-around Olympic champion, entertained the
Palma audience and the judges with her elegant moves in a soft and
gentle music background to win the last event of the floor
exercise, scoring a title winning score of 9.775 points.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the women's team title and her ealier all-around
crown, the 1.68-meter Russian also triumphed in the uneven bars by
executing a wide-open flurent routine for a day-high 9.800 points.
</P>
<P>
"I am really happy to win the gold medals and it's surely out
of my expectation," said the sole four-time champion in the on-
going University Games, which are being smeared by insufficent
transportation and media services.
</P>
<P>
Her compatriot Elena Produnova struck gold in the other two
women's individual events by scoring 9.562 and 9.700 points from
the vault and beam respectively.
</P>
<P>
With 19-year-old Nikolai Krioukov took two golds out of six men
's apparatuses, the Russian gymnasts collected a lion's share of
eight gold medals out of the 14 gymnastic titles at stake.
</P>
<P>
Krioukov came out last in the hirozontal bar but scored the
best of 9.675 points after he triumphed first in the parallel bars
with 9.700 points.
</P>
<P>
Belarus took two men's individual golds through Vitali
Rudnitski in the floor exercise with 9.625 points and Ivan Ivankov
in the rings with 9.800.
</P>
<P>
While the other two gold medals were split by Romania and Cuba
as Marius Daniel Urzica choked up the first gold for Romania by
scoring 9.750 points from the pommel horse and Abel Driggs of Cuba
was awarded the crown in the vault with 9.625 points.
</P>
<P>
China, a gymnastic powerhouse but represented here with a
second-string squad, was denied its first gold medal as Dong Zhen
who scored 9.800 from the rings in the team competition, was only
awarded 9.750 points despite his clearly better performance, said
gymnastic expert Gao Jian, chef de mission of the Chinese sports
delegation.
</P>
<P>
"However, we don't want to complain anything and we have to
find the solution to the dire fact that the Chinese gymnasts,
especially the women, are unable to keep their forms for a longer
period whenever they are getting older," said Gao Jian.
</P>
<P>
"We're a little bit pity that our gymnasts failed to win any
single gold medal," said Chinese coach Pan Chenfei. "But it's
understandable for several reasons."
</P>
<P>
While other gymnasts powers have all sent in their best
athletes to Palma, China only fielded in its second-string squads
despite some namesakes of world titles, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, the gymnastic competitions is usually prone to
mistakes and is also judged subjectively without clear criteria
which even allow a critical margin of some 0.400 points,"
explained coach Pan.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xuan, China's other bet for gold medal, dropped twice from
her speciality of the beam wherein she was crowned in the 1998
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
As the gymnasts are backing away from Palma, the Russians
collected eight golds, leaving only six to the others whereas
Belarussians took two, and Romania, Cuba, Japan and Ukraine had
one apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
