<HEADLINE> Russians Sweep Women's Gymnastic Titles in Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Svetlana
Khorkina spearheaded her compatriots to make a clean sweep of the
women's gymnastic titles to enable Russia to overtake the United
States in the overall gold tally, while China choked up its first-
ever gold medal from the diving competitions at the 20th World
University Games here Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Khorkina, the all-around Olympic champion, entertained the
Palma audience and the judges with her elegant moves in a soft and
gentle music background to win the last event of the floor
exercise with 9.775.
</P>
<P>
With the women's team title and the all-around crown in her bag,
the 1.68-meter Russian also triumphed in the uneven bars by
executing a wide-open flurent routine for a day-high 9.800 points
to become the sole four-time champion.
</P>
<P>
"I am really happy to win the gold medals and it's surely out
of my expectation," said Khorkina.
</P>
<P>
Her compatriot Elena Produnova struck gold in the other two
women's individual events by scoring 9.562 and 9.700 points from
the vault and beam events respectively.
</P>
<P>
And as the 19-year-old Nikolai Krioukov took two golds out of
six men's apparatuses, the Russian gymnasts collected a lion's
share of eight out of the 14 gymnastics gold medals at stake.
</P>
<P>
Krioukov came out last in the hirozontal bar but scored the
best of 9.675 points after he triumphed first in the parallel bars
with 9.700 points.
</P>
<P>
Belarus took two men's individual golds through Vitali
Rudnitski in the floor exercise with 9.625 points and Ivan Ivankov
in the rings with 9.800 points.
</P>
<P>
While the other two gold medals were split by Romania and Cuba
as Marius Daniel Urzica choked up the first gold for Romania by
scoring 9.750 points from the pommel horse and Abel Driggs of Cuba
was awarded the crown in the vault with 9.625 points.
</P>
<P>
China, a gymnastic powerhouse but represented in Palma with a
second-string squad was denied a first gold medal as Dong Zhen who
scored 9.800 from the rings in the team competition, was only
awarded 9.750 points despite his clearly better performance, said
gymnastic expert Gao Jian, chef de mission of the Chinese sports
delegation.
</P>
<P>
"However, we don't want to complain anything and we have to
find the solution to the dire fact that the Chinese gymnasts,
especially the women, are unable to keep their forms for a longer
period whenever they are getting older," said Gao.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xuan, China's other bet for gold medal, dropped twice from
her speciality of the beam wherein she was crowned in the 1998
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
As the gymnasts are backing away from Palma, the Russians
collected eight golds, leaving only six to the others whereas
Belarussians took two, Romania, Cuba, Japan and Ukraine had one
apiece.
</P>
<P>
However, China eventually pocketed its first gold through Wang
Feng in the men's one-meter springboard as the diving competitions
started today.
</P>
<P>
The swimming pool was no longer the bonanza for the United
States as it only got one out of six gold medals at stake of the
day, by taking the women's 4x100 meters freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
The Russians took two swimming titles, the men's 100m freestyle
and 100m breaststroke, dethroning the United States for the first
time in the gold tally by 12-9.
</P>
<P>
The other three titles were split by Japan, South Africa and
the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Russian also triumphed in the women's epee invididual event as
Oksana Ermakova outscored her Ukrainian compatriot N. Grouzinskaia
15-14.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese women's volleyball team outscored their Spanish
peers by three straight sets for the top spot in the group, while
their men's counterparts beat Norway 3-1 for the second victory
out of four outings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
