<HEADLINE> Two Wounded in Old U.S. Base Explosion in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 6 (Xinhua) -- An explosion wounded two people
on Monday in the Old U.S. military base in Rio Hato, around 120
kilometers southeast of the capital, Panama's authorities said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred when a worker was piling up stakes in
the base, where a private company is carrying out a reforestation
program.
</P>
<P>
The worker lost an eye as a result of the explosion, in
addition to serious wounds in the face, neck, thorax and right
hand. Another worker who was close by at the time of the incident
also suffered injuries.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said that unexploded ammunitions were left
abandoned by the U.S. military when they left the base.
</P>
<P>
The explosion happened at a time when the Panamanian
authorities are take actions for compensation from the United
States for the clean-up job.
</P>
<P>
Under the Torrijos-Carter treaty signed between the two
countries in 1997, U.S. military bases in Panama will be handed
over to Panama on December 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
