<HEADLINE> China Win First Gold Through Diving at Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A cramp on his calf failed to
hinder Wang Feng from capturing China's first gold when he
somersaulted to win the men's one-meter springboard title in the
20th World University Games here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Wang, 20, capped his performance with his final dive, a tucked
backward two and a half somersaults which earned him a field-high
score of 77.520 points.
</P>
<P>
Leading all the way, Wang finally garnered 402.60 points for
the gold, also the first of China in the Games.
</P>
<P>
Philippe Comtois of Canada won the silver with 377.88 points
and Dean Pullar of Australia was third in 358.86.
</P>
<P>
"The field was rather strong, and fortunately I brought out my
best," Wang said after the victory.
</P>
<P>
He grimaced in the semi-finals when his left calf suddenly
suffered from cramp. His coach Zhong Shaozhen massaged his
suffered leg and told him to concentrate on the competition.
</P>
<P>
"As the competition was held at night in the open air, the
temperature fall caused his cramp, and I just advised him to hold
on," Zhong said.
</P>
<P>
"At this juncture, we should try to win the gold at any cost,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
China's diving juggernauts just cranked up with his win, Wang
said. "We at least can win three other golds, in men's three-
meter springboard, women's platform and three-meter springboard,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
