<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ACPC Meeting Opens in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Vice President Marco
Maciel announced here Tuesday the opening of the special session
of the Association of Coffee Producing Countries (ACPC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting, lasting from Tuesday to Wednesday, will evaluate
the results of the last meeting of the International Coffee
Organization (ICO), which was held in May this year in London and
focused on international cooperation and market stability.
</P>
<P>
"Brazil recognizes its important role as the largest coffee
producer, and will not leave to one side this leadership, which it
must exercise to guarantee the highest possible integration of
producer countries".
</P>
<P>
The ICO, made up of 49 producing countries and 18 coffee
consuming countries, is the only organization in the sector
authorized by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the largest coffee producer and exporter in the world,
and is also the second largest consumer of the grain. During the
1998-1999 year, Brazil consumed 12.2 million bags of coffee (60
kilograms per bag) and exported 21 million bags, earning 2.8
billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
