<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Steps up Anti-Corruption Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has step
up the anti-corruption campaign, uncovering more than 3,025 cases
of corruption involving 7.21 trillion rupiah (1.07 billion U.S.
dollars) in state funds during the 1998/1999 fiscal year ending
last March.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Development Supervision and State
Administrative Reforms Hartarto said after a meeting with
President B.J. Habibie here on Tuesday that 594 corruption cases
were at the prosecution stage, while thousands of others were
still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto, who leads the national drive against corruption,
nepotism and cronyism, Justice Minister/State Secretary Muladi and
acting Attorney General Ismudjoko and Minister of Information
Muhammad Yunus reported to Habibie on the progress of the
anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
They also briefed the president on the measures that have been
and would be taken to prevent and manage corruption in government
offices and state companies, according to national newspapers
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on strategic efforts to combat corruption, Muladi
said Habibie enacted on Tuesday four government regulations and
one decree to guide the enforcement of Law No.28/1999 on Good
Governance. The law will come into effect on November 20.
</P>
<P>
"The Presidential decree will set up a commission in charge of
keeping the records of and auditing the assets of government
officials. The commission will start working on May 20, 2000,"
Muladi said.
</P>
<P>
From this date, all government officials would be required to
declare and report their personal assets to the commission and to
have their assets audited by the commission, he said.
</P>
<P>
Muladi said the law also encouraged public participation in the
drive against corruption by legally protecting people who reported
the conduct of officials.
</P>
<P>
On former president Soeharto corruption probe, acting Attorney
General Ismudjoko said his office was still investigating the case
and focusing on the misuse of state-owned funds by several charity
foundations once led by Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
"Another focus is the abuse of power by the former president.
For example the policy of exempting a certain industry from the
obligation to pay taxes according to existing regulations," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Under Soeharto, who was forced down in May last year, corrupt,
collusive and nepotistic practices flourished in the country, The
Indonesian Observer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Predicts Higher Petroleum Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The petroleum price will surpass 12.
50 U.S. dollars per barrel by the end of the year, the Venezuelan
newspaper "El Universal" quoted official sources as saying on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The recuperation of the basket is nearing 12 dollars; at the
moment the average is 11.85 dollars per barrel", said Minister for
Energy and Mines Ali Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that any profits arising from a price of more
than 9 dollars per barrel will be directed to the Inversion and
Stabilization of Macro-economic Fund (ISMF), reassuring that the
Ministry of Energy and Mines won't hold dogmatic positions on the
matter of oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0114 </DOCNO>
