<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Discover Ancient Tomb in Jiangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists recently unearthed a
tomb dating to the Southern dynasties (420-589 A.D.) in Ganzhou,
east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists surmise that the tomb, which is seven meters long
and 1.91 meters wide, was built for a wealthy businessman. The
tomb was constructed of 10,000 bricks with varying designs and the
structure's semi-spherical roof can easily bear the weight of an
automobile local source said.
</P>
<P>
Excavation work has led to the recovery of two bronze and
porcelain pieces.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists note that the tomb reflects the high standard of
construction skills and burial practices during the dynasty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Semiconductor Sales Up in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide sales of
semiconductors reached 11.28 billion U.S. dollars in May, up
almost 12 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released Tuesday by the U.S.
Semiconductor Industry Association (SIA), the Asian market and
Japan outstripped the global growth rate. The Asian market
excluding Japan showed an accelerated increase of 18 percent, with
revenues totaling 2.35 billion dollars. Japan was up 15.3 percent,
with two billion dollars of sales.
</P>
<P>
The SIA described the global double-digit increase as a clear
indication of the positive and solid growth of the semiconductor
industry, which experienced downturns in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Also in May, chip sales in the Americas increased 11.2 percent,
and Europe was up 3.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
