<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Cancels Central American Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan government has
canceled the Central American Summit scheduled for next week, due
to tension with Costa Rica, local reports said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Nicaragua was to pass the pro tempore
presidency of the Central American Integration Secretariat to
Costa Rica in line with the six-month rotational presidency
agreement, whereby its five member countries share the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman was quoted Tuesday by the
media here as saying that there still lack the correct conditions
for the summit, adding that his regional counterparts understand
the situation.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Nicaraguan Public Security Minister Juan Rafael
Lizano lodged strong protests against Costa Rica in a declaration
in which he said Aleman had threatened to kill any Costa Rican
police who carried arms on the San Juan River border.
</P>
<P>
The transit rights along the San Juan river are the most
contentious issue between the two countries. The present treaties
give Nicaragua sovereignty over the waterway, but also grant Costa
Rica the right of free transit.
</P>
<P>
However, the implementation of the right has become a
disputable political problem, as Nicaragua considers that this
right of free transit is given only for commercial purposes, and
not for the transit of armed guards.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican Foreign Ministry has maintained silent over
protests from Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Costa Rican police removed 300 families from the
Costa Rican capital, many of which were Nicaraguan immigrants, and
expelled 33 Nicaraguans.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican Foreign Ministry said it believes there are
some 600,000 Nicaraguans residing in Costa Rica, the majority of
whom are undocumented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhelin Reservoir Set for Tourism Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province
recently announced plans to transform the Zhelin Reservoir into a
300 sq. km scenic area.
</P>
<P>
The local government in Yongxiu County has introduced a series
of preferential policies to encourage the participation of both
domestic and foreign investors in the development program.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir, located some 100 km north of Nanchang, the
provincial capital, is Asia's largest water conservancy project
with an earthen dam. The area features approximately 1,000
picturesque islands.
</P>
<P>
The Zhenru Temple complex, a well-known Buddhist temple, and
Poyang Lake attract millions of migratory birds each year.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for introducing various tour itineraries such as
bird-watching, forest expeditions and tours of fishing villages.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of investors from outside the province
have exhibited interest in the project and one entrepreneur from
east China's Zhejiang Province recently inked a contract to
develop Feilong Island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
