<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakian Economic Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The growth of Slovakian economy has
apparently slowed down since the beginning of this year, giving
the country a very difficult time.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report by the National Statistics Bureau,
Slovakia's gross domestic product (GDP) in the first three months
was 178.2 billion crown (about 4.1 billion U.S. dollars), a meager
1.8 percent hike over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Being the slowest growing period in five years, the target of
three percent GDP increase set for 1999 will surely not be
realized. Economists expect the figure to go below one percent.
</P>
<P>
The Slovakian economy enjoyed a high increase between 1995-97
when its GDP growth rate registered at least six percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the year 1998 witnessed a bad turn, with GDP growth
rate dropping to 4.4 percent. At the same time, the country began
facing big deficits in the national finance and foreign trade, as
well as high foreign debts, devaluation of crown and sliding of
the industrial and agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Now the country has already taken measures to stop the economic
situation from worsening, such as giving up the seven-month-old
zero taxation system on June 1 and collecting seven percent tax to
all imports, with an aim of quick recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0129 </DOCNO>
