<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief of U.N. Military Advisors Arrives in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the United Nations
Military Advisors for the August direct vote in East Timor Brig.
Gen. Rezagul Haider arrived in Dili, capital of East Timor, on
Tuesday along with 15 other personnel.
</P>
<P>
"The military advisors will be deployed at the UNAMET (United
Nations Assistance Mission for East Timor) offices in 13
districts," UNAMET spokesman Ueki Yashuiro was quoted by Antara
News Agency Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Countries contributing military advisors to UNAMET include
Bangladesh, Australia, Malaysia, Denmark and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Philippines Ambassador to Indonesia Leonides T. Caday who
recently visited East Timor said the Philippines government is
obliged to participate in UNAMET and assist Indonesia in the
popular consultation process.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16 Filipinos are now involved in UNAMET's operation,
including six with civilian police, while 10 are U.N. staff
members, mostly in charge of administrative matters.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Indonesia, Portugal and the U.N.
on May 5, the U.N. will send civilian police advisers from several
countries to assist Indonesian police in maintaining law and
order.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is fielding a mission of 900, including 270 civilian
police, 50 military officers and hundreds of electoral officials
and administrators to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Foreign Minister Ali Alatas Tuesday stated that
according to the tripartite agreement in New York, there is no
plan to deploy U.N. troops to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Speculation on the possibility of the U.N. deploying a
peacekeeping force to East Timor was raised following Sunday's
attack on U.N. staff and volunteers in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Although violence and attacks often take place in East Timor,
Alatas explained that the U.N. is yet to declare the territory as
insecure.
</P>
<P>
The government would continue to strive for a conducive climate
for the direct ballot in East Timor scheduled for August 22, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The ballot will allow the territory's people to choose whether
their homeland should become an autonomous region within Indonesia
or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the U.N., which
still considers Portugal as the administering power of the
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
