<HEADLINE> Forty-nine Italian Cities to Be Car-free on European Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Forty-nine Italian cities will take
part in the activity of "City Without My Car" on the European Day
of September 22, the Italian Ministry for the Environment
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The cities include Rome, Turin, Naples, Palermo and Florence,
while Milan will make the final decision by July 16 if it will
participate in the initiative asking people to leave their cars
unused that day.
</P>
<P>
Participating cities must decide on the areas where traffic
will be limited, and what alternatives, including shuttle buses,
bicycles and electric vehicles, will be offered to residents and
visitors,
</P>
<P>
The project, beginning from this year, will be repeated on the
same day in 2000, when more European nations will be involved.
</P>
<P>
France now has the biggest number of cities, 65, taking part in
the activity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
