<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Customs Moves to Support Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Beijing Customs will improve services and increase efficiency
to facilitate the municipality's export business, and will
introduce priority treatment for key export-oriented enterprises,"
said Mao Xintang, deputy director of Beijing Customs.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises engaged in new and hi-tech industries will also be
granted preferential treatment to enhance equipment imports. A
special office will be established to administer related
enterprises, with tax breaks and exemptions available for some
enterprises, said Mao.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises enjoys tax rebates for exports will receive refunds
in a timely manner, and the management of export processing
businesses will be computerized and improved, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Customs is also expected to reform its system for
Customs entry procedures in order to improve efficiency.
Electronic Customs entry procedures will also be expanded to
facilitate trade, said Mao.
</P>
<P>
He added that supervision of Customs officials will be
strengthened, and abuse of power cases will be dealt with harshly.
</P>
<P>
The capital's foreign trade sector entered a recovery period in
May, with continuing growth for general trade, an upturn in
processing trade reporting and expanded exports to the United
States, Russia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show Beijing's May foreign trade volume hit
623 million U.S. dollars, up 21.7 percent on last year. Exports
grew 15.2 percent on an annual basis to 273 million U.S. dollars,
with imports surging 27.3 percent to 350 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
