<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Be Awarded Half World Cup Berth, Says Blatter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Asia has been granted a play-off
slot against a European team that could see their contingent
boosted to five at the 2002 World Cup, Sepp Blatter, president of
soccer's world governing body FIFA, confirmed in Los Angeles on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan and South Korea, as co-hosts in the first World Cup to be
staged in Asia, automatically each qualify for a place but Asian
football chiefs had been dismal that only two more countries would
win a spot under the original plans.
</P>
<P>
Following two days of meetings of FIFA's Executive Committee,
Blatter said UEFA president Lennart Johansson agreed to have the
14th-placed team in European qualifiers play off with the fifth-
placed team in Asian qualifiers for the final berth in the World
Cup. The defending champions France will qualify automatically.
</P>
<P>
The move should avert a threatened boycott of qualifying by the
Asian Football Confederation (AFC).
</P>
<P>
But Johansson's offer needs to be approved by the UEFA
Executive Committee set for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"If Europe dose not agree, Asia will have to maintain its
current position to reconsider its participation in 2002 (
qualifying)," FIFA vice-president and South Korean Football
Association president Chung Moon-joon was quoted as saying. "It's
not easy to be optimistic."
</P>
<P>
AFC general secretary Peter Velappan expressed his happiness.
"I myself am personally satisfied with the magnanimous offer,"
Velappan was quoted as saying. "I have to take the word of the
FIFA president," he said.
</P>
<P>
The AFC also had to approve the deal and discuss the matter
with its 45 delegates on Thursday, one day prior to FIFA's
Extraordinary Congress, according to Velappan.
</P>
<P>
Last December, FIFA allocated the 32 berths for 2002 Finals
among the six regional confederations. Europe received the same
number of berths of 15 it had in 1998, and CONCACAF and Africa
were also awarded their same 1998 allocations of three and five.
</P>
<P>
South America had it reduced from five to 4 1-2, requiring it
to play the Oceania champion for a fifth berth. For 1998, the
Oceania champion was required to play the fourth-placed team from
Asia, which resulted in Iran beating Australia.
</P>
<P>
Asia's allotment went from 3 1-2 to four. But it's allocation
included the first-ever co-hosts, Japan and South Korea, leaving
Asia's 43 other members to fight it out for two remaining berths.
</P>
<P>
The AFC wishes to have three guaranteed places in addition to
automatic qualifiers Japan and South Korea, and threatened to
boycott qualifying, while allowing Japan and South Korea to
participate in the finals, if its demand was not met.
</P>
<P>
But Velappan later said it would accept a half berth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan to Host Int'l Symposium on Ming Dynasty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth International Symposium
on the History of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) will be held in
Shimen County, Hunan Province, between August 15-22.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, sponsored by the China Society of Ming Dynasty
History, is widely recognized as the most authoritative academic
conference on related studies.
</P>
<P>
The society reports that more than 250 domestic and foreign
experts and specialists on the history of Ming Dynasty, including
representatives from countries such as the United States, Germany,
Japan and the Republic of Korea, as well as Hong Kong, Macao and
Taiwan regions, will attend the event.
</P>
<P>
Participants will discuss wide-ranging topics ranging from
political, economic, cultural and foreign relations practices
during the Ming Dynasty to the peasant uprising in the latter part
of the period.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yuanzhang, a native of Fengyang in east China's Anhui
Province, founded the Ming Dynasty and was later overthrown during
a peasant uprising led by Li Zicheng, a native of Mizhi in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Li Zicheng lived a life of seclusion in Shimen County following
his overthrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
