<HEADLINE> Israel to Treat Young Hebei Heart Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
to send 10 young poverty-stricken heart patients to Israel for
free treatment each year beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Liu Gang, a 12-year-old boy suffering from congenital heart
disease, will soon receive his first-ever professional treatment
in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Matat, an Israeli charity organization, is sponsoring the "Save
A Child" project with the support of the Israeli Ministry of
Foreign Affairs. The organization sent a delegation of medical
experts to the province last March to conduct a lecture series and
provide free surgery for 10 Chinese children suffering from heart
problems.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 young patients have visited the Hebei Children's
Hospital for examinations in recent years. However, only 200
children have received operations due to limited medical
facilities. The situation prompted Matat to sign an agreement
pledging to provide financial aid which enable 10 children receive
treatment in Israel each year.
</P>
<P>
Matat will select candidates based on medical records supplied
by the province.
</P>
<P>
The organization has also offered financial aid and
technological support to a hospital in Lanzhou, northwest China's
Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
Matat has established relations of cooperation with the Tel
Aviv University, an institution well-known for its coronary
surgery department, and has completed preparations for the arrival
of the first 10 Chinese youngsters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
