<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Expels 33 Athletes From SEA Squad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Sports Council
(KONI) has decided to expel 33 athletes from its original 448-
strong team for the 20th Southeast Asian (SEA) Games in Brunei
Darussalam next month, due to the athletes' poor show during pre-
Games training.
</P>
<P>
Mochammad Hindarto, a KONI official in charge of the athletes
development program, said 11 track and field athletes, four female
squash players and 18 female field hockey players had been
expelled after a discussion between KONI and sports organizations
concerned.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto said that the attendants of the discussion predicted
that that the 415-strong team was expected to win some 65 to 70
gold medals at the Games.
</P>
<P>
"But sports organizations' officials were low-keyed on their
targets and said they could win 58 golds at the most," he was
quoted by The Jakarta Post Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto said that 12 of the 20 sports were expected to strike
gold, including track and field, badminton, billiards and snooker,
boxing, cycling, karate, pencak silat, swimming, table tennis,
taekwondo, tennis and traditional boat racing.
</P>
<P>
Such other sports as basketball, bowling, golf, hockey,
shooting, soccer, sepak takraw and squash could hope for bronze
medals.
</P>
<P>
KONI also urged the Badminton Association of Indonesia (PBSI)
to include men's singles player Taufik Hidayat in the SEA Games
squad.
</P>
<P>
"We have difficulties earning gold in Brunei. If our shuttlers
can make a clean sweep of the seven golds, why should they only
target five?" Hindarto said.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto said if PBSI fielded Taufik, Indonesia would be
hopeful of a clean sweep, as the 19-year-old player stood a good
chance of winning the men's singles and contributing to men's team
victory.
</P>
<P>
PBSI official in charge of athletes development program
Mangombar Ferdinand Siregar said Taufik needed to take a break
after his poor performance in the Sudirman Cup and World
Championships. "Taufik is focusing on the Olympics, along with
Hendrawan and Budi Santoso. PBSI has a big responsibility to win
gold at the Olympics. We'll see how he manages to overcome his
psychological barrier after both major events in the Indonesia
Open in September in Bali," Siregar said.
</P>
<P>
He said despite a strong opposition, PBSI was looking forward
to a repetition of an Indonesian clean sweep of titles two years
ago. "But we shouldn't be careless, because we have priorities in
the Olympics and Thomas and Uber Cup championships," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
