<HEADLINE> Philippines' Mayon Volcano Causes Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Mayon Volcano in the central
Philippines caused one low frequency earthquake and one high
frequency volcanic tremor for the past 24 hours, Philippine
Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A report of Phivolcs issued at 8:00 a.m. said the volcano is
still in restive condition on Tuesday with instruments of Phivolcs
detected sulfur dioxide flux of about 4,660 tons and sustained
inflationary trend along the southeast slope.
</P>
<P>
For the past 24 hours, Mayon's activity was characterize by
weak to moderate steam emission of about 100 to 150 meters from
the peak of the volcano, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Alert level one is still in effect and volcanologist warned the
public to strictly observe the 6-km Permanent Danger Zone and the
one-kilometer safety buffer zone extension in the southeast slope.
</P>
<P>
Looming over half a dozen towns in Albay Province, Mayon
erupted on June 22 without warning, releasing cauliflower-like
clouds from its crater and forcing thousands of local residents to
flee from home.
</P>
<P>
The volcano has erupted 45 times in the past 360 years with the
deadliest in 1814 buried a whole town and killed 1,200 villagers.
At least 77 people were killed in its last major eruption in 1993.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
