<HEADLINE> Chinese Arctic Expedition Encounters Fresh Water Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Snow Dragon, an
expeditionary vessel which is carrying 124 Chinese scientists and
journalists to the North Pole, has encountered problems with a
pump used to produce fresh water.
</P>
<P>
The ship's daily fresh water production capacity has dropped
from 25 to 15 tons, according to Captain Yuan Shaohong.
</P>
<P>
The Snow Dragon departed Shanghai on July 1 and the estimated
daily consumption for the voyage was set at 28 tons.
</P>
<P>
"Maintenance personnel are currently attempting to repair the
pump," Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
The Snow Dragon, an icebreaker which has completed five voyages
to the South Pole, enjoyed calm waters as it passed through the
Sea of Japan and has traveled 1,115 nautical miles since last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ship treats sewage prior to release and burns waste paper
in an incinerator. Other waste materials, including glass, iron
and plastic, will be returned to Shanghai for treatment, said Yuan.
</P>
<P>
The expedition, China's first scientific investigation in the
Arctic region, will last 68 days. The Snow Dragon is expected to
enter the Arctic Ocean by the middle of this month.
</P>
<P>
The expedition has attracted wide attention both at home and
abroad, with team members receiving numerous e-mail message from
overseas Chinese.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
