<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Central Bank to Issue Bonds Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's central bank, Bank
Indonesia (BI) will issue bonds again in a bid to collect funds
for the economic development in the country, BI Deputy Governor
Miranda Gultom said.
</P>
<P>
Miranda did not say how much the bank will issue, but confirmed
here Tuesday that the bonds will be with a fixed interest rate of
12 percent for five years and 14 percent for ten years in 2000.
The variable rates will be issued in 16 series, the Business News
bulletin Wednesday quoted Miranda as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There will be wider option on the capital market next year with
BI's plan to issue bonds as one of the money market instruments
which are much demanded, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Indonesian government has issued bonds worth about
18 trillion rupiah (2.6 billion U.S. dollars). The value is too
small to create the secondary market, according to Miranda.
</P>
<P>
Concerning bank recapitalization, she expressed the confidence
that the implementation of the recapitalization program will
completely overcome the banking problem by the end of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
