<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia to Finish Assessing War Damages in Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia will finish assessing
in six months the war damages it suffered during the savage NATO
bombings from March 24 to June 9, Development, Science and
Environment Minister Jagos Zelenovic announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Uniform assessment sheets will soon be distributed to all legal
persons in the country's two republics, which are required to hand
in the finished sheets in two months, said Zelenovic, also leader
of the national assessment committee.
</P>
<P>
Assessment committees of each republic should make a
comprehensive report on the matter before December 26, six months
after the country announced the end of the state of war on June 24,
Zelenovic added.
</P>
<P>
During its 78-day bombings, NATO flew more than 20,000 flights,
dropped 21,000 tons of bombs and launched 1,300 missiles against
Yugoslavia, a small country of 100,000 square kilometers and 11
million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
