<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Twelve-Year-Old Chinese Girl Becomes World's Best Young Letter Writer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A moving letter by a 12-year-old
Shanghai girl, China, won her the "world's best letter" award in
the 28th annual international letter-writing competition sponsored
by the Universal Postal Union (UPU) and the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Chen Xinyi, the first-prize winner in the competition for young
people up to the age of 15, told about the valuable role the
postal service has played in keeping her in touch with her sick
Korean friend.
</P>
<P>
The UNESCO jury described Chen's letter as moving and touching,
full of tender images with attractive and rich descriptions, the
UPU said in a press release here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This year's international letter-writing competition coincides
with the UPU's 125th anniversary and the 22nd UPU Congress in
Beijing, China.
</P>
<P>
Chen will receive a gold medal from UPU Director-General Thomas
E. Leavey at a special ceremony to celebrate the organization's
125th anniversary during the UPU Congress on September 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The second prize was awarded to 14-year-old Maria Kyratzi from
Cyprus while a 14-year-old girl from Vietnam, To Hong Van, won the
third prize.
</P>
<P>
Silver and bronze medals will, as in the past, be awarded to
the second and third prize winners on the World Post Day on
October 9 in their respective countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
