<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vitamin A Derivative Shows Potential in Treating Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Researchers here have found
that a synthetic vitamin A derivative may form the basis for an
entirely new type of chemotherapy to help fight cancers.
</P>
<P>
Understanding how the derivative, fenretinide, works will allow
doctors to more effectively use this promising drug, said a report
in the July 7 issue of the Journal of the National Cancer
Institute. The report was authored by researchers at the Children
Hospital Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
The researchers are currently leading a clinical trial to find
the appropriate dose of fenretinide in children. The National
Cancer Institute recently approved a nationwide clinical trial to
test the anti-tumor activity of fenretinide against the childhood
cancer neuroblastoma.
</P>
<P>
Studies were made of various levels of fenretinide on the tumor
cells, including measurements of a special molecule called
ceramide. Ceramide can kill tumor cells, but researchers have not
previously found any relatively non-toxic drug that can cause
large amounts of ceramide to be made in cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
The results showed that fenretinide markedly reduced the
survival of the cancer cells even under reduced oxygen conditions.
Furthermore, fenretinide caused ceramide levels to increase up to
10-fold. The greater the amount of fenretinide used, the greater
the rise in ceramide, and the greater the amount of tumor cell
killing.
</P>
<P>
The results also showed that fenretinide could kill tumor cells
that were resistant to many common anti-cancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
The researchers suggest that combining fenretinide with other
drugs, which can specifically enhance the anti-tumor action of
ceramide, might be a powerful new way to fight cancers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Resumes Production of Maize Meal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean millers who shut down
their plants for over two weeks have resumed full production of
staple maize meal following negotiations with the government last
week.
</P>
<P>
Misheck Nyamupingidza, chairman of the Millers' Association of
Zimbabwe, confirmed Tuesday that maize milling had resumed while
negotiations continued, the daily Herald reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said millers were "nicely negotiating" with the government
and were now waiting for communication from the Ministry of
Industry and Commerce on the best way forward.
</P>
<P>
Millers stopped production on June 22, pressing for a 61.2
percent increase in the price of maize meal. The government had
approved a 20 percent increase effective last month and another 20
percent to be effective in September.
</P>
<P>
But the millers said they could no longer mill the product
profitably due to the 88 percent increase in the floor price of
maize.
</P>
<P>
Failure to break the deadlock between the two parties resulted
in the closure of the mills last month.
</P>
<P>
To maintain viability in the industry, millers and the
government have tentatively agreed that the price of maize meal
would go up by five percent every month until December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
