<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Economic Recovery to Sustain: MAS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's fledging economic
recovery is expected to be sustained into next year, the Monetary
Authority of Singapore (MAS) announced in its annual report
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Prospects for a sustained economic recovery into the second
half of 1999 and beyond are good," said Koh Yong Guan, managing
director of MAS, at a press conference on the 1998/1999 report.
</P>
<P>
He said that the external environment is expected to be
favorable and the policy measures taken last year in response to
the economic slowdown are beginning to take effect.
</P>
<P>
Encouraging signs for the Singapore economy were the robustness
of the U.S. economy and expectations of a soft landing there, as
well as an increase in exports from many crisis-hit economies, Koh
said.
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned that despite the favorable outlook, Singapore
was not completely out of the woods yet.
</P>
<P>
"First, the recovery is not yet across the board," said Koh.
"Although the manufacturing sector expanded by 6.5 percent in the
first quarter, construction, commerce and most financial services
remained weak."
</P>
<P>
"Second, the positive outlook hinged on continued strength in
the industrial countries and a recovery in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
There are risk factors to watch out for, particularly a sharp
correction in the U.S. stock market, a weakening of the Japanese
yen and rising protectionist pressures, according to the annual
report.
</P>
<P>
Singapore must remain watchful of business costs even as the
economy picks up, Koh said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and MAS Chairman Lee Hsien Loong
announced Tuesday that the government will reassess the economy at
the end of this year to decide whether to begin restoring the
employer's Central Provident Fund contribution rate one year in
advance.
</P>
<P>
Lee also stated that the government will review its growth
forecast for this year in August as the economy is picking up
faster than expected.
</P>
<P>
The current official forecast for this year's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) is a growth of between zero and two percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
