<HEADLINE> Common Australia-New Zealand Currency to Be Studied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australia-New Zealand
Business Council will set up a high-powered committee to determine
whether a common currency for Australia and New Zealand would be
good for business.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion Wednesday quoted Council Chairman David Truscott
as saying that the group may study other common currency
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, a number of business people and economists in
New Zealand have advocated a unified currency with Australia,
saying it would bring "important benefits" to the country.
</P>
<P>
Governor Don Brash of New Zealand Reserve Bank told the
Parliament's finance and expenditure select committee in March
that there are "some important benefits in a currency union" with
Australia.
</P>
<P>
"What I'm saying is let's discuss the pros and cons with all
the benefits and all the costs on the table," he told the
committee.
</P>
<P>
Although Prime Minister Jenny Shipley has said the issue is not
on the agenda of her government, some of her cabinet ministers
have come out in favor of a debate.
</P>
<P>
"We've decided we need to do it by stages ... a lot of people
are going to jump to the end and say we're going to be the seventh
state of Australia. We want to look at the currency issues and
issues that perhaps surround that, rather than get involved in
political issues like statehood," the Wellington-based newspaper
quoted Truscott as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the progressive study will involve the business
community and interested government departments, and critics of a
common currency will be invited to participate.
</P>
<P>
Truscott is also national president and Auckland president of
the Commerce Chamber of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, a small Wellington-based working
party will meet next week to set a study framework. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Province Ready to Fight Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin Province
is actively preparing for possible severe flooding this summer,
and sufficient anti-flood materials have been put aside for
possible flood-control fight.
</P>
<P>
Devastating flooding affected the province last summer, causing
great economic losses. Meteorologists said they can not rule out
the possibility of severe flooding this summer, and tornado, mud-
rock flow, and mountain torrents may also hit the eastern
mountainous areas in the province.
</P>
<P>
Great efforts have been put into the re-building of water
control facilities since the floods receded, and all the
waterspouts have been reconstructed and water control facilities
damanged by flooding restored.
</P>
<P>
The water control departments at all levels have dispatched
nearly 800 officials to inspect the flood-control facilities, and
the province also put more than 27 million yuan into 15 expedient
flood-control projects, which are expected to be completed before
the flooding season.
</P>
<P>
According to Jilin's vice-governor Yang Qingcai, the People's
Liberation Army units and armed police stationed in the province
are both fully prepared for the anti-flood fight, and another 800,
000 civilians have also been organized for urgent flood relief
missions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
