<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Set to Study North Pole Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists will
study the interaction of ice, air and sea in the Arctic Ocean as a
part of China's first government-organized scientific
investigation of the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
The study will offer scientists insight to the influence the
Arctic has on global climate changes, according to Xie Simei, a
female team member from the State Oceanic Environment Forecast
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
The research will not only focus on the ocean and the polar ice
cap, but also on the exposed ice surface, according to Xie.
</P>
<P>
"Studying the ice surface, the most sensitive feature subject
to global climate changes, is quite difficult," she said.
</P>
<P>
Xie, 58, is the oldest of the three female scientists
participating in the expedition.
</P>
<P>
The Snow Dragon, an icebreaker which has completed five
previous voyages to the South Pole expeditions, is equipped with
an advanced meteorological monitoring laboratory which allows for
real time observations of the ocean, air and ice.
</P>
<P>
Xie added that extensive research data will be published
following the expedition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
