<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators Discover Cause Of Major Fire In Southern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A major factory fire that killed
16 people and injured eight last month in the city of Shenzhen in
south China's Guangdong Province was caused by a rectifier on a
fluorescent lamp, a special investigation team announced today.
</P>
<P>
The team also said that faulty management practices were partly
to blame for the fatal fire that engulfed the Zhimao Electronics
Plant, a Taiwanese-funded firm in the city's Bao'an District, on
June 12.
</P>
<P>
The investigators interviewed eye witnesses and obtained a
great deal of evidence in their examination of the premises. They
said that the fluorescent light that was attached to a beam above
a pile of flammable paper in a distant part of a warehouse on the
first floor fell and the heat of the rectifier ignited the
flammable articles and the flames spread throughout the whole
factory.
</P>
<P>
The investigators also concluded that the accident was the
indirect result of the factory owners' disregard for safety
regulations and sloppy management.
</P>
<P>
The persons responsible for the disaster are being sought for
possible criminal involvement.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen held a city-wide general check of safety soon
afterwards on 28,915 enterprises, construction sites, restaurants,
markets, shops, and rental houses and found problems in 5,009
places.
</P>
<P>
It issued 3,574 citations to get people to deal with the
trouble spots, shut down 17 boilers that were found to have
serious problems, demolished 34,000 sq.m. of construction work
that violated regulations, and levied 400,000 yuan (48,309 U.S.
dollars) in fines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
