<HEADLINE> Kenya Heightens Vigilance Along Border with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Five Kenyan navy ships, along with
three fast-attack craft, are keeping vigil along the Kenya-Somalia
marine border since last week.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the Kenyan navy has been placed on
such alert, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The vessels left Kenya's Indian Ocean port Mombasa with orders
to intercept any hostile boats or ships from the Somali militia
and have been conducting "aggressive patrols" near the border,
said Nicholas Simani, spokesman for the Department of Defense,
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Although the conflict had been resolved, the (Kenyan) armed
forces were maintaining their state of preparedness along the
borders in the case of recurring hostilities," said Simani.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's combat vessels are equipped with a missle system that
has a range of 200 kilometers and the capacity of strike deep into
the heart of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi gave Somali militia
an ultimatum to return stolen firearms and vehicles. They were
returned before Kenya's full retaliatory attacks could be
launched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
