<HEADLINE> Kenyan Food Prices Expected to Rise: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The minister told the parliament Tuesday that there was
likelihood of a poor food production as a result of the La Nina
weather phenomenon and the effects of army worms which ravaged
crops in most provinces in the country, media reports said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A shortfall of 1.5 million bags (each bag weighs about 90
kilograms) is expected in grain production from the normal three
million bags, he said, adding that levels of food production would
depend on the performance of the rains between now and September.
</P>
<P>
"This shortfall is likely to exert pressure on food prices and
it may have to be met through imports," said Mudavadi.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that his ministry, in conjunction with the
Treasury, was strengthening the capacity to deal with such
disasters, and called for support to the agricultural sector,
especially against unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
The minister also asked the parliament to approve a total of
4.7 billion shillings (around 67 million U.S. dollars) for
recurrent and development expenditure up to June next year.
</P>
