<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Import Oil Products from Yemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will import oil
products from Yemen to satisfy the demands of its own and the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam-based Tanganyika Oil Investment Co. will
import more than 20,000 tons of petrol, diesel and kerosene from
the wells of Marib and Masile in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The firm has finished the procedures required to start
importing the products, and construction of a petrol station with
the capability to preserve 50,000 tons of oil is nearing
completion, the Financial Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania is not far from Yemen, and automatically transport
costs are reduced, giving an advantage in the pricing of the
product," Ally Balbahou, the company director, told the Tanzanian
weekly paper last week.
</P>
<P>
The director recently paid a five-day visit to Yemen to contact
 suppliers as well as concerned authorities.
</P>
<P>
Apart from selling oil locally, the company will sell any oil
in excess to neighboring countries, he said. Tanzania has eight
neighbors, six of which are landlocked countries.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's oil supplies mainly rely on imports. Several foreign
 companies are exploring offshore oil in Tanzania, so far without
any significant discoveries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
