<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Police to Protect U.N. Personnel in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian military pledged to
give direct protection to U.N. Mission personnel in East Timor, a
spokesman said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The assurance was made by Indonesian Defense Minister and Armed
Forces Chief General Wiranto when meeting with the chairman of the
U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET), Ian Martin, here for talks
about the security situation in the troubled territory ahead of
the U.N.-administered direct ballot on autonomy in August.
</P>
<P>
"The security responsibility is fully handled by the Indonesian
police who will give protection to all parties, including the
UNAMET officials," military spokesman Brig. Gen. Sudrajat quoted
Wiranto as saying after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto also said that the Indonesian police contingent,
deployed to help create and maintain security in East Timor
before, during and after the ballot, will be provided with
motorcycles to enable them to give direct protection to the UNAMET
officials.
</P>
<P>
Martin said after the meeting that "he (Wiranto) will also be
making other security changes, including continuing the process of
replacing Indonesian military forces with Indonesian police."
</P>
<P>
In the near future, Indonesia will again deploy 1,200 police
officers to replace 10 military companies in the territory
covering 32,200 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
So far, Jakarta has sent 1,961 police officers to replace seven
military companies which were pulled out in two stages, namely, on
June 6 and June 25, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Martin said his presence here is to express to the highest
levels of the Indonesian government the United Nations' serious
concerns regarding the security situation in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, he said he touched on the stoning attack of
a UNAMET outpost in the Bobonaro district town of Maliana, and the
Sunday raid by a pro-integration group on a humanitarian convoy in
Liquica Last week.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the United Nations' desire to back up the
whole process of the August ballot which paves the way for the
East Timorese to determine their own future.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, Jakarta offered special status based on
wide ranging autonomy to the people of East Timor through the
popular consultation. If a majority of the East Timorese reject
the offer of autonomy, East Timor, which was integrated into
Indonesian in 1976, will peacefully separate from Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DRC's Military Commission to Be Monitored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The belligerents in the conflict of
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have set up a committee to
monitor the mandate of the Joint Military Commission and the
United Nations peacekeeping forces in the country after the
signing of the ceasefire agreement.
</P>
<P>
The committee was established Tuesday evening after the peace
talks in Lusaka took a new twist when Uganda, Rwanda and some of
the rebel groups of the DRC changed their demands and requested
for the exclusion of the United Nations peacekeeping forces once
the ceasefire agreement is signed, Zambian newspapers reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, parties attending the peace talks are deadlocked
over the thorny issue of disarming the Interahamwe militiamen
operating from bases inside the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Zimbabwe differed seriously on who should be given
the mandate to supervise the disarming of the ex-Rwandan soldiers
mainly Hutus who were responsible for the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Zimbabwe wanted the U.N. peacekeeping forces to be
sent to the DRC after signing the ceasefire, to be responsible for
enforcing peace.
</P>
<P>
But Uganda and some rebel factions have refused this, demanding
that the belligerents in the conflict should be the ones to disarm
the Interahamwe.
</P>
<P>
Many expressed fears that if the Interrahamwe were not properly
 demobilized they would still continue to wreak havoc.
</P>
<P>
By Tuesday evening, the impasse had not been resolved as
consultations continued. This continued to put on hold the
plenary meeting for ministers of defense, home and foreign
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day Zimbabwean and Ugandan officials were
engaged in a meeting trying to resolve the problem but with little
achievement.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the meeting said Rwandan and Ugandan delegates
 attending the peace talks are expected to leave Zambia Wednesday
for home to consult with their leaders concerning the ceasefire
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting starting last Monday was attended by
defense, home and foreign affairs ministers from the 14 Southern
African Development Community (SADC) member states, as well as
Rwanda, Uganda and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the ceasefire agreement which was initially
scheduled for June 26 has been delayed due to a number of
differences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
