<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 08:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Says U.N. Worker Involved in Sabotage Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has accused a U.N. employee
working in northern Iraq of being involved in acts of sabotage,
said Iraqi newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An authorized Iraqi Foreign Ministry source said Reed Ayan
Proteen, a New Zealander, attempted to spread agriculture pests in
northern Iraq, said the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has summoned U.N. Coordinator in Iraq Hans Von
Sponeck and handed him a memorandum of protest calling for
ordering Proteen out of Iraq within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
Proteen is a supervisor at the U.N. Office of Project Services
(UNOPS) which is entrusted with removing land mines in northern
Iraq's Suleimaniya province.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi source said Proteen entered Kalar subdistrict in
Suleimaniya in April this year, and buried several boxes of
suspicious material nearby.
</P>
<P>
The source said that residents in that area later dug out
those boxes and found that the boxes were containing eggs of
locusts.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government condemned the act and demanded
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan investigate it to reveal all the
parties involved, said the source, adding the Iraqi government
also demands that Proteen be put on trial.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has repeatedly accused United States and British
nationals working in northern Iraq, particularly those working
with non-governmental organizations, of spying on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Iraq asked the U.N. to replace U.S. and
British nationals working with U.N. agencies in central and
southern Iraq with staff of other nationalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
