<HEADLINE> More Chinese High-School Grads Expected To Enter College(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- About 3.4 million graduating
high school students in China started the 3-day national college
entrance exams today.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of them are from single-child families, whose
parents have great hopes for them.
</P>
<P>
The parents of one 18-year-old boy said they've made him do
everything he can on his own ever since he was still a child to
make him independent and able to adapt better in society.
</P>
<P>
Because of the family planning policy of the late 70s, parents
can provide their children with better living conditions and more
opportunities to develop, and this year, a large number of the
high school students are taking the literature, art, and physical
education exams.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education has decided to increase enrollments
by 330,000, from the original 1.3 million, meaning that 50 percent
of those who take the exam in Guangdong Province will be able to
go to college, and in Hebei and Shandong it will be 40 percent. (
more)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese High-School Grads Expected to Enter College (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Parents seem less relaxed than their children and many still
consider the entrance exam a crucial part their child's future.
One unemployed worker said that he didn't get much of an education
because of Cultural Revolution, so he wants his daughter to pass
the exams and to have a brighter future.
</P>
<P>
Parents these days try their best to provide a better study
environment for their children before the exams and some even get
a hotel room to allow their child to spend the hot days in more
comfortable surroundings.
</P>
<P>
City governments have some policies that help the students,
like prohibiting noise in residential areas, lower hotel room
rates, free transportation, and psychological counseling hotlines
to reduce the pressure on students.
</P>
<P>
The 3-day exams will cover Chinese, Politics, History, English,
Mathematics, Physics, and Chemistry. About 3.2 million high school
students took the entrance exams last year, and 1.08 million
entered college or university.  
</P>
</TEXT>
