<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Sharif Facing Uphill Task to Sell Deal on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif is facing an uphill task to sell his deal with U.S.
President Bill Clinton to defuse tension with India over Kashmir
as their joint statement has drawn mixed responses at home over
the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Sharif flew to Washington in the wee hours of Sunday and held
extensive talks with the U.S. president on what was reported the
single agenda of the crisis in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Described by the media as a rather positive outcome of the
short visit, the two sides issued a joint statement which said,
"concrete steps will be taken for the restoration of the Line of
Control (LoC) in accordance with the Simla Agreement."
</P>
<P>
While explaining "concrete steps", Pakistan's Foreign Office
spokesman Tariq Altaf indicated that Pakistan would appeal to and
use its influence with the Kashmiri Mujahideen (freedom fighters)
to stop fighting in Kargil and vacate the areas under their
control.
</P>
<P>
This was the only "concrete step" Pakistan was expected to take
as envisaged in the joint statement after the three-hour talks
between Sharif and Clinton, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Altaf also said that Pakistan has agreed to do so as it
believed the Kashmiri "freedom fighters" had achieved their
objectives of internationalizing the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Altaf, however, disagreed with the U.S. interpretation that
Pakistan was supposed to withdraw its troops from Kargil. He
stressed that Pakistan had never crossed the LoC, and this kind of
interpretation is "mischievous".
</P>
<P>
Observers here are of the view that it is by any means a
welcome step that Pakistan, although it always held the Mujahideen
are not under its control, has agreed to persuade them to stop
fighting in Kargil.
</P>
<P>
It is conducive to defusing the continuing tension along the
LoC and creating an environment favorable for resumption of the
bilateral dialogue process with India which had once been on right
track after the signing of the Lahore Declaration in February this
year.
</P>
<P>
Fighting erupted along the LoC in early May when India accused
Pakistan of sending "infiltrators" across the LoC occupying some
strategic heights in Kargil.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, however, denied the accusation, saying that it had
never crossed the LoC and there was no question of sending its
troops into India-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
It held that the so-called infiltrators are Kashmiri freedom
fighters who are fighting for their right to self-determination as
bestowed to them by the relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The two rival neighbors have since been trading intense
artillery fire across the LoC, along with large-scale Indian
ground and air force operations against the Mujahideen in the
Kargil sector.
</P>
<P>
The tensions along the LoC remain high and the two armies are
engaged in a dangerous all-round confrontation as the diplomatic
efforts by Pakistan failed to achieve any substantial results
because of the sharp divergence of the two sides on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The "Sharif-Clinton deal", as Pakistan's media termed, has
surprisingly met with divided responses at home.
</P>
<P>
Government sources believe that Prime Minister Sharif has
succeeded in internationalizing the Kashmir issue, as Pakistan had
always desired.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the Sharif government has been
successful in convincing the international community that the
Kashmir issue is a potential threat to peace and security in South
Asia which cannot be ignored especially after the nuclearization
of the region.
</P>
<P>
Major opposition parties, who had supported the government on
the Kashmir conflict, are now very much critical of the latest
development. They believe that Sharif's Washington tour is a
"major setback" Pakistan has sustained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some Kashmiri groups have rejected the joint
statement between Pakistan and the United States, vowing to
continue fighting against the Indian forces.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Nawaz Sharif, who is still touring overseas to
convince the world leaders on Pakistan's position on the Kashmir
issue, faces an uphill task at home to defend his deal with
Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Complete Siberian Tiger Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of natural habitats for Siberian tigers have shrank
from six to three since the early 1990s, with only two remaining
natural habitats for leopards which once roamed throughout the
mountain range.
</P>
<P>
"The survey attributes the shrinking population of tigers and
leopards, as well as the dramatic reduction in natural habitats,
to the increasing human population and logging activities,"
according to Yang Shihe, an official from the Jilin Wildlife
Protection Association.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP-funded survey covered 71,000 sq.km. in the Changbai
Mountains. The survey team used advanced technology to carry out
applied field research.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government plans to establish a system of nature
reserves to protect the remaining Siberian tigers and leopards.
</P>
<P>
Siberian tigers are on the list of the world's 10 most-
endangered species, with an estimated 300 animals surviving in
Russia, northeast China and the northern part of the Korean
Peninsula. A recent survey revealed that northeast China is
currently home to some 20-odd Siberian tigers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Province Increasing Flood Fight Ability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- All major highways have been
reopened and electricity and telecommunications basically restored
in China's Zhejiang Province, one of the provinces hit most by
this year's floods, thanks to the efforts of some five million
people.
</P>
<P>
Flood fighters are now busy repairing damaged water
conservation projects and reinforcing levees, while farmers are
trying to replant rice seedlings.
</P>
<P>
A source at the Zhejiang Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters says that the province still faces a difficult task
since water levels in most rivers and lakes in the northern part
are still above the danger line and many people are still besieged
by floodwaters, even though the heavy rains have stopped.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang had had uninterrupted rainfall since the beginning of
the rainy season in early June and total rainfall in some areas
was as high as 806 mm, three times the normal amount for rainy
season.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains caused heavy flooding in some 45 cities and
counties in northern Zhejiang, where water levels on all major
rivers and reservoirs hit all-time highs.
</P>
<P>
The floods have destroyed 18,000 houses, damaged 3,900
kilometers of levees, and inundated 478,000 hectares of farmland,
affecting the lives of 7.9 million of the 43 million local people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
