<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Calls for Closer People-to-People Contacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga stressed here Wednesday the
need for closer people-to-people contacts in South Asia to promote
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly feel that the countries of our region, with a
common cultural heritage, should be able to let our people
interact freely," she told a special session of the Federation of
Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga noted that the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) network so far has proved very helpful in
bringing its member countries together.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, I must emphasize the need for our people to
get together more closely," she said. "It is difficult to promote
regional cooperation by mere agreement among political leaders,
bureaucrats and elite of our countries."
</P>
<P>
"We need to get our people to meet each other and come to
understand and respect each other. We can build togetherness and
camaraderie," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
She again called for full liberalization of travel among the
SAARC countries -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka, especially by lifting needless
restrictions on travel visas and "totally incomprehensible
restrictions on inter-country transport facilities."
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan president held that free interaction among
peoples in the region will promote peace as well as "strengthen us
to face the challenges of globalization" by promoting meaningful
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
She praised the work of the SAARC Chamber of Commerce and
Industry as very fruitful in this regard. She requested the
regional apex body to fully develop this cooperation and extend it
from the businesses to the people at large.
</P>
<P>
"You can also promote investment in our countries so that we
can exploit our complementarities to the benefit of our region,"
she said of the SAARC apex body.
</P>
<P>
SAARC leaders have always stressed the promotion of
people-to-people contact in the region to strengthen mutual
understanding and goodwill among the peoples.
</P>
<P>
A number of initiatives have been taken in this regard, which
include the SAARC scheme for promotion of organized tourism, SAARC
chairs, fellowships and scholarships scheme and SAARC visa
exemption scheme.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga arrived here Monday on a four-day state visit at
the invitation of King Birendra. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Condemns Turkish Troops Incursion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi Foreign Ministry on
Wednesday condemned fresh Turkish troops incursion of northern
Iraq, calling it "a serious defiance of the U.N. Charter and rules
of the international law."
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman said that last Saturday some
10,000 Turkish troops, supported by tanks, armoured vehicles,
helicopters and warplanes, invaded Iraq's northern territories,
the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"This invasion is part of repeated series carried out by
the Turkish forces against Iraq since 1991 and is coincided
with the feverish military aggression acts being perpetrated by
America and Britain against Iraq," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Turkish government to withdraw its troops
immediately and desist from repeating such aggressive acts which
are contrary to the U.N. Charter and principles of the
international law.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War, the Iraqi government lost its control
of the northern Kurdish autonomous region, and Turkish troops
often crossed the border into northern Iraq to chase rebels of the
outlawed Turkish Kurdish Workers' Party.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman warned Turkey against consequences of its
assistance to the U.S. and British warplanes which have been
carrying out raids on northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's parliament last month agreed to extend the presence of
U.S. and British air forces in a Turkish air base to patrol the
northern no-fly zone in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
following the Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the Kurds
in the north and Shiite Muslims in the south from possible
attacks by the Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman warned that "the Iraqi government retains
its full right to retaliate this aggressive act in proper time
and venue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
