<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall Further in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued falling in
Tokyo Wednesday, dragged down by continued profit-taking following
recent gains, with the key Nikkei index closing below 18,000 for
the first time in three days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, which lost 84.33 points
Tuesday,dropped 91.83 points, or 0.51 percent, to end at 17,958.90.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, went down 1.70 points or 0.11 percent to 1,
477.02.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section declined to 644.96 million shares
from Tuesday's 675.03 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Fuji Bank was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented technology issues were generally higher,
supported by the U.S. dollar's strength against the yen, while
high-priced issues weakened on profit-taking, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Arbitrage-linked selling, stirred by a drop in index futures
prices, was another factor leading overall share prices lower,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers narrowly
exceeded gainers 595 to 580, with 152 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
