<HEADLINE> Iran's Population Growth Still "Alarming," </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran's population growth rate is
still "alarming" despite its achievements in population control
during the past decade, a senior U.N. official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is still alarming with the consideration of the young
status of the Iranian population," Mohammad Mosleh-Uddin,
representative of the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) in
Iran, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian Statistics Center, Iran's population
growth rate will jump to 1.7 percent by the end of 2001 from the
present 1.4 percent, as 52 percent of Iran's 63-million population
are below 20 and will be reaching in marriage and childbearing age
soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mosleh-Uddin praised the Iranian government for its success in
reducing the population growth rate from 3.2 percent in 1986 to
1.4 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA has decided to allocate some 11 million U.S. dollars
to Iran in its third five-year plan to start in the year 2000,
with an aim to promoting the quality of family planning services
in Iran with strengthened cooperation between the UNFPA and Iran,
the representative said.
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA will also promote its activities in Iran's rural
areas since half of the Iranian population are living in these
provinces, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
