<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanctions, "Against Muslim People": Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan ruling Taliban
Wednesday termed the U.S. sanctions an "attack against Muslim
people", according to a report reaching here from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed an executive order Monday
imposing financial sanctions upon the Taliban militia in
retaliation for their support of suspected terrorist Osama bin
Laden.
</P>
<P>
The United States imposed sanctions because it "wants to attack
the Muslim people", said Taliban spokesman Maulvi Faizl Mohammed
Faizan, adding that "all of their accusations against the Islamic
Emirate of Afghanistan and against bin Laden is without reason and
without evidence."
</P>
<P>
"America does not want a Muslim government in Afghanistan,"
observed Faizan.
</P>
<P>
Last month Washington put Osama on the FBI's "Ten Most Wanted
list" and offered a 5 million dollars reward for information
leading to his arrest.
</P>
<P>
Washington accuses Osama of masterminding last year's bomb
attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to the Taliban, Osama, who left his home in
Afghanistan's southern Kandahar earlier this year, has disappeared
and his whereabouts is unknown.
</P>
<P>
But the United States recently claimed Osama is still in
Afghanistan and receiving support from the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
"It is surprising... we are in Afghanistan and we don't know
where Osama is. But Clinton who is thousands of miles away says he
knows where he is. Where is his proof?" Faizan questioned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Calls for Free Trade in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga stressed here Wednesday that
free trade will be beneficial to all the South Asian countries in
the age of globalization.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that developing nations like ours should act in
unison in facing the challenges of globalization. Hence, we have
been strongly advocating a preferential trade area in our SAARC
region," Kumaratunga told a special session of the Federation of
Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
"It will be very necessary for us to be together, if we're to
face the challenge of this new feature of globalization," she
said.
</P>
<P>
As proposed by Sri Lanka, a SAARC Preferential Trading
Arrangement (SAPTA) was formulated and entered into force in
December 1995. Three rounds of trade talks have been completed
under it, offering over 5,700 commodities for preferential
treatment in the SAARC member states -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India,
the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga, who is the current SAARC chairperson, told a press
conference that it stands true that SAPTA is not completed yet but
"it is moving forward very slowly."
</P>
<P>
"It can move forward more positively and faster," she said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Sri Lanka is the first country in South
Asia to have totally liberalized its tariffs unilaterally. "Our
unilateral trade liberalization has not led to a disruption of our
domestic economy," she said.
</P>
<P>
The fourth round of trade talks under SAPTA is scheduled to
start this month in the Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
SAARC leaders had preferred to set up a South Asian Free Trade
Area by 2001 but deferred it indefinitely at their Colombo summit
in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga came here Monday for a four-day state visit at the
invitation of King Birendra. She visited the SAARC Secretariat
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
