<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Dip on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices continued tumbling
on the Singapore Stock Market Wednesday as the investors continued
dumping small cap stocks after many brokerage houses imposed
limits on buying.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) ended 30.98 points
lower to close at 2,144.53.
</P>
<P>
The volume totaled 1,139.93 million shares valued at 1,236.69
million Singapore dollars (727.06 million U.S. dollars). Losers
outnumbered gainers by 338 to 34 with 75 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Hotung led the active chart of the day with 77.10 million
shares changing hands. It was followed by AFP that had 55.23
million units done. IPC was the next with 53.34 counters traded.
</P>
<P>
OCBC F led the gainers, rising 30 cents to close at 14.60
Singapore dollars. CityDev ran up 20 cents to finish at 11.50
Singapore dollars. ASJ Hldgs was up 18 cents to end at 1.15
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Bukit Sem headed the descent of the day
shedding 100 cents to close at 17.30 Singapore dollars. DBS F lost
90 cents to finish at 20.30 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 dropped 80
cents to end at 30.60 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the optimism of a market rally appeared
waning as concerns over an overheated market started taking over.
</P>
<P>
They said in the broad market all sector indices were lower and
initial support from property and bank shares diminished as more
selling orders poured in, pulling the key index lower.
</P>
<P>
Feeling that penny stocks had been overbought after the market
steamed ahead 54 percent higher this year, many investors began
panic-selling this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
