<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lao Government Endeavors to Protect Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- To mark the National Wildlife
Conservation Day (July 13), the Lao Ministry of
Agriculture-Forestry (MAF) has issued an order banning hunting
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Under the order, according to a report of Lao official news
agency KPL Wednesday, people are prohibited from hunting, selling
or buying any kind of wild animals from August 28 to October 25,
which is the mating season for many wildlife species in Laos.
</P>
<P>
"Sale in the markets of any product derived from animals killed
in the wild is prohibited," the order said.
</P>
<P>
During fish spawning season, the Lao government requires each
locality to take measures to ban people from catching fish and
from blocking the path of fish swimming upstream to lay their
eggs.
</P>
<P>
It is illegal to use bombs, poisons and any small-hole nets to
catch fish, said the order, adding that the law on animal
conservation would be brought to local people and explained to
them.
</P>
<P>
People will be encouraged to continue to hand over voluntarily
their hunting guns and other hunting equipment to local
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Lao National Wildlife Conservation Day was established on
July 13, 1997 to protect wildlife and fish.
</P>
<P>
However, because of the increased awareness of the issue, most
agriculture officials admit that hunting in Laos has considerably
decreased over the last few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
