<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK To Promote IT Entrepreneurship Among Youngsters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government,
together with local industrial community and academic institutions,
launched a new program here Wednesday to encourage Hong Kong's
young people to go in for the information technology industry.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) attended the launching ceremony of the
Information Technology Entrepreneur Program (ITEP) Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
ITEP is a one-year program designed for young and ambitious
individuals with sound business ideas, the right mindset and
adequate skills in information technology and service development.
</P>
<P>
The program is operated by the Information Technology
Entrepreneurs Association, a non-profit organization founded by
the Chinese University of Hong Kong, the Hong Kong University of
Science and Technology and the University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It is open to anyone who can work legally in Hong Kong,
although university graduates, particularly students from IT-
related fields, are expected to be a majority among the applicants.
</P>
<P>
A total funding of 25 million HK dollars (3.2 million U.S.
dollars) will be sought for the first five years of the program.
</P>
<P>
About one half of the funding is provided by the Industrial
Support Fund of the government and the remaining funding will rely
on industrial sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
So far, the program has obtained sponsorship and pledges of
over 5.3 million HK dollars (679,487 U.S. dollars) from industry
and academic institutions.
</P>
<P>
The program is launched in response to the report by the Chief
Executive's Commission on Innovation and Technology and the
Digital 21 IT strategy of the SAR government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
