<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Candidate Agrees to Let Rival Serve WTO Term First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 7 (Xinhua) - Thai Deputy Prime Minister and
Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said here Wednesday that
he agreed to let his arch rival first serve as the WTO's
director-general if a term-sharing compromise could be reached.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said he would agree to serve the second term if he was
allowed a role in formulating policy beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Supachai and New Zealand's Mike Moore have been locked in a
bitter battle for the director-generalship of the WTO for more
than eight months.
</P>
<P>
An Australian plan to end the deadlock is now on the table and
if, accepted, would see Moore and Supachai take turns in the top
job.
</P>
<P>
As the Thai government is undergoing a cabinet reshuffle,
Supachai is being urged by the ruling Democrat party, of which he
is a member, to take any second term offered to him.
</P>
<P>
But he could make the decision only after a WTO general council
meeting, scheduled for Thursday, in which supporters of the rival
candidates are expected to come up with a compromise over the
shared term proposal.
</P>
<P>
Supachai also suggested that the two terms be longer than two
years -- half the normal four year term for a WTO leader.
</P>
<P>
Pressure to find a new WTO leader is building as crucial talks
are looming in November in Seattle which are intended to kick
start a new round of global trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Western nations including the United States and some European
countries are backing Moore but much of Asia has put its weight
behind Supachai, making consensus so far impossible among the
WTO's 134 members.
</P>
<P>
Thailand had proposed to end the deadlock by vote, which was
ruled out by the United States. But the United States has so far
not blocked a plan for sharing the post of director-general.
</P>
<P>
The WTO has been without a director general since Italy's
Renato Ruggiero stepped down at the end of April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
