<HEADLINE> No Done Deal With Marcoses: Estrada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
maintained Wednesday there is no done deal for a compromise
settlement between the government and the heirs of the late
president Ferdinand Marcos over their alleged ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio program, the president branded as lies and
misinformation reports claiming such a deal has been forged.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is that we have not reached any deal with the Marcos
family," Estrada assured the public, saying all negotiations
related to the recovery of the alleged money will be conducted
with full transparency.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that he will not keep the people in the dark about
developments pertaining to government efforts to repossess all
assets that rightfully belong to the country.
</P>
<P>
"We will not withhold any detail from the people. I am
committed to transparency and full disclosure in all government
negotiations. If there is a deal we will make it public," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Since last week Estrada and the Presidential Palace officials
have denied reports alleging that a compromise settlement is ready
to be inked with the Marcoses as early as October.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that both Executive Secretary Ronaldo
Zamora and the Presidential Commission on Good Government, which
takes charge of government efforts to trace and recover all
ill-gotten assets, have belied the existence of the reported deal.
</P>
<P>
However, former first lady Imelda Marcos insisted that a
compromise agreement between her family and the administration was
in the bag.
</P>
<P>
"It was just a matter of due process of the law. After that, it
is all finished," she told the country's Inquirer newspaper
Tuesday. 
