<HEADLINE> First UK Troops Start Pullout From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of British troops are to be
withdrawn from Kosovo as the first wave of reducing British forces
in the Yugoslav province, Defense Secretary George Robertson said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a written answer to a parliamentary question, Robertson said
the pullout would start on Friday as now the province has been
secured.
</P>
<P>
He said logistics and support staff of the 5th Airborne Brigade
would start to pull out on Wednesday. They are to be followed by
some of the helicopter support force.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of the 700 soldiers from the battered southern
Yugoslav province had always been planned, he said.
</P>
<P>
The troops were used as part of the initial advance into Kosovo
but are no longer needed by KFOR commanders, he said.
</P>
<P>
The KFOR force will still have 10,000 UK troops in its ranks,
and that could increase to 13,000 as more troops go in.
</P>
<P>
The multinational NATO-led Kosovo force, known as KFOR and
commanded by British General Mike Jackson, totals about 25,000 at
present and will stand at 50,000 when it is up to full strength.
</P>
</TEXT>
