<HEADLINE> Malawian President Urged Election Losers to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakili Muluzi
has urged those who lost in the elections, which he described as
free and fair, to accept defeat and start helping him build the
nation.
</P>
<P>
The president, reacting to post-election violence, advised
Malawians to reject any individual who is against national unity
as an enemy of democracy and freedom.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to entertain any ideas that cause division or
violence amongst our people," he cautioned at Chichiri Stadium on
the occasion of the commemoration of the 35th anniversary of
independence which falls on Tuesday, the Malawi News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We must work together as one people. We must be united," the
president told the huge crowd that came to witness the occasion.
</P>
<P>
As leader of the Malawian nation, he strongly condemned all
those "who stand for hatred or violence and are bent on dividing
us."
</P>
<P>
"You can count on me who will lead this country without regard
to what part of our country one comes from and without regard to
race, color, gender or disability," said Muluzi.
</P>
<P>
The president also thanked Malawians for expressing their
confidence and faith in him to lead the country for another five
years.
</P>
<P>
He advised those honored with responsibility to take their task
 seriously "otherwise we have no right to occupy these leadership
positions."
</P>
<P>
Malawians have a right to prosperity, development, education,
health care and protection from crime and violence, he observed.
</P>
<P>
"My re-election administration has a duty and obligation to
provide the kind of climate which will make it possible to meet
the needs of all our people," pledged the president. 
</P>
