<HEADLINE> Thailand Striker Pursues Premier League Dream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai footballer Kiatisak Senamuang
is bidding to follow the Asian trail blazed by several Japanese
and Chinese stars to make a mark in European professional squads.
</P>
<P>
The striker, also skipper of the national team, has started a
two-week trial with English Premier League Middlesborough, which
is managed by Manchester United legend Bryan Robson.
</P>
<P>
Those Asian footballers who have forced their way into European
clubs include Japanese Hidetoshi Nakata of Italy's Perugia,
Chinese Fan Zhiyi and Sun Jihai of English first division Crystal
Palace and Yang Chen of Germany first division Frankfur.
</P>
<P>
"If I have the chance I would certainly go to play with other
foreign teams again," Kiatisak said before he left for England on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's national team coach, Peter Withe, a former Aston
Villa and England striker, said he believed Kiatisak had the
ability to make a mark in English football.
</P>
<P>
"His speed and tactical awareness are good enough for the
Premier League. His desire will help him to succeed." Withe was
quoted as saying in the local reports.
</P>
<P>
Kiatisak, 26, nicknamed "Zico" after the great Brazilian,
emerged to fame when he led Thailand to the gold medal at the
Southeast Asian Games in Singapore six years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Boro spotted Kiatisak on a pre-season tour of Thailand two
years ago." Robson was quoted as saying in the Thai press.
</P>
<P>
"We just thought we would have a look at him," said the coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
