<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges New Israeli Government to Resume Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has
urged the newly-formed Israeli government to implement the Wye
accord signed with the Palestinians and resume peace talks with
Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hours after Israeli Labor leader Ehud Barak was sworn in as
prime minister Tuesday night, Mubarak said he hopes the new
Israeli government will soon take steps to break the deadlock in
the Arab-Israeli peace talks, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader made the remarks in an interview with the
French Le Figaro newspaper, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel signed in October, 1998 the Wye
accord, under which Israel should pull back from another 13
percent of the West Bank. But the former government of the
hardline Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu halted the military
withdrawals in December.
</P>
<P>
Barak has pledged to advance the peace talks with the
Palestinians, reactivate the negotiations with Syria, which have
been stalled since early 1996, and bring back Israeli troops from
Lebanon in a year.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called for the rebuilding of confidence in the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He praised Barak as a man who "has all qualifications necessary
to" make progress in the peace-making, expressing belief that the
peace process will move forward.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak underlined that the Palestinian issue is the core of
the Arab-Israeli conflict, dismissing concerns that the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks will outshine the Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
Reaching a solution to the Palestinian issue will help solve
the problems on the other tracks of talks, the Egyptian leader
maintained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
