<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Announces New Strategies to Boost Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Ministry of Commerce
announced new strategies on Wednesday to boost export of the
country's major agricultural products next year, the Thailand News
Agency (TNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The products include rice, tapioca, rubber and maize.
</P>
<P>
The TNA quoted a high-ranking official of the ministry as
saying the strategies include launching a contest of fragrant rice
strains nationwide to select the best strain of rice.
</P>
<P>
The strain would then be promoted and distributed among local
farmers to increase its production for exports next year.
</P>
<P>
The government recently projected that the overall exports of
Thai rice this year will reach 5.5 million tons, slightly over its
target of 5.3 million tons due to agreed orders, through
government-to-government contracts, of about 700,000 tons of Thai
rice.
</P>
<P>
For tapioca, the strategies would be focused on not only
promoting exports of the product to trading partners, but also
finding new markets.
</P>
<P>
Strategies for rubber included campaigns to promote Thai rubber
products worldwide.
</P>
<P>
As for maize, strategies would be emphasized on promoting the
production to meet the country's demand of about 5 million tons
next year and exporting the rest to foreign markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
