<HEADLINE> Israeli Prime Minister Launches Peace Initiatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- In a sign that he will move to
renew the peace process quickly as pledged, Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak Wednesday set meetings with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser
Arafat soon.
</P>
<P>
Barak will travel to the Egyptian port city of Alexandria
Friday to meet Mubarak and hold a meeting with Arafat Sunday at
the Erez Crossing between Israel and the Palestinian-ruled Gaza
Strip, the Government Press Office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet King Abdullah Bin Hussein of Jordan next week
and intends to leave for the United States in 10 days for talks
with President Bill Clinton and other senior U.S. officials, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The initiatives came one day after Barak was sworn in as prime
minister in the Knesset (parliament), which approved his
seven-party coalition government formed following more than six
weeks of grueling talks.
</P>
<P>
While presenting his government for approval, Barak appealed
to Arab leaders to move quickly to reach peace with Israel and
promised to give same priorities to talks with the Palestinians
and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Syrian leaders have expressed their willingness
to resume peace talks with Israel, which were largely frozen in
the three-year tenure of the former hard-line Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan, the two Arab neighbors which have signed
peace treaties with Israel, have pledged to play active roles in
helping advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman praised Barak's initiatives
Wednesday, calling it a development "in the right direction."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
