<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Equestrian Officials Found to Receive Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The investigation has found that
three of Japanese equestrian officials received money from a rider
seeking to be on the 1992 Olympic team, according to reports on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Equestrian Federation met at its headquarters in
Tokyo to discuss an in-house investigation into a report in the
Mainichi newspaper this week that Yoshinaga Sakurai paid three
federation members about 3.5 million yen (29,000 U.S. dollars) to
be selected for the team that went to the Barcelona Games.
</P>
<P>
Federation head Shozo Hara told reporters that the
investigation found that the three officials had received the cash
but that the gifts had no influence on picking the team.
</P>
<P>
The federation will decide on any penalties at a meeting of
senior officials Monday, Hara said.
</P>
<P>
Hara criticized the allegations as unfair.
</P>
<P>
According to the investigation, one official who had served as
Sakurai's coach received the money as a gift long after Sakurai
had already been selected on the team. The money that went to
another official went into expenses for setting up a base training
camp for Sakurai.
</P>
<P>
The third official, who has offered to resign from his post,
borrowed the money from Sakurai and is planning to pay it back,
the federation said.
</P>
<P>
Sakurai also denied the payments were meant to get him a berth
on the team, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Launch Small Enterprise Capital Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- After several months of delay, the
Philippine Stock Exchange (PSE) has finally decided to launch the
much-awaited small and medium enterprise (SME) capital market
later this year.
</P>
<P>
The SME capital market is a separate listing board established
within the PSE to allow small and medium-sized companies with high
growth potentials to raise capital by selling their shares to the
public.
</P>
<P>
Jose Fernando Alcantara, PSE vice president for the business
development and information group, told a meeting on Wednesday
that the PSE is now studying the behavior of the SMEs,
particularly how they do business in the market.
</P>
<P>
Alcantara said he believes that with the coming in of the SME
capital market, the PSE will be facing more challenges ahead
considering that SMEs will likely be prone to business-related
problems because they are still new in the market.
</P>
<P>
He noted that once the SME capital market is finally working,
the PSE management will have no choice but to put more minds and
eyes to monitor the activities of the listed SMEs.
</P>
<P>
So far, he said, the first batch of five SMEs, were initially
listed by the PSE's SME board. This batch was carefully chosen
from a total of 25 applications that the PSE received from the
various SMEs in the country.
</P>
<P>
PSE officials are optimistic that the new SME board will
contribute to the further development of the capital market
because it will be an inexpensive source of capital for the SMEs.
</P>
<P>
They said that through the PSE facilities, the SMEs may sell
their shares to the public by way of what is called an initial
public offering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Mini-Summit in 2nd Day Amid Optimistic Atmosphere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The mini-summit in Togolese capital
Lome entered the second day Wednesday amid strong signs that a
peace deal to end Sierra Leone's civil war may be imminent.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo left Lome last night but
promised to return Wednesday to re-join the talks, according to
information reaching here Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Presidents from Nigeria, Liberia, Burkina Faso and Togo held
separate talks with President Tejan Kabbah of Sierra Leone and
rebel leader Foday Sankoh Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Togolese foreign minister said Tuesday night, according to an
unconfirmed report, that the final documents might be produced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main difference between Kabbah-led government and
Sankoh-led Revolutionary United Front had been how to form a
four-year transitional government.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, especially some field commanders, think the Kabbah
government's offer of four cabinet seats was "not enough".
</P>
<P>
The People's War Council, a body representing them had been
asking at least seven ministerial posts and a vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have also required an internationally guaranteed
amnesty for their alleged war crimes.
</P>
<P>
Despite the differences, Sankoh did not rule out that a
compromise agreement might be worked out "within the next few
days". "I'm not excluding anything," he said before the starting
of the summit.
</P>
<P>
The rebel commanders in the Sierra Leone bushes were consulted
last week by RUF negotiators, and a high-ranking representative of
the commanders jetted in to Lome Tuesday night to join the summit.
</P>
<P>
Whether the Nigeria-led west Africa Peacekeeping forces which
restored Kabbah to power in 1998 after an armed coup is also under
discussion in the summit between the relevant parties, information
reaching here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Legislature Condemns U.S. Anti-China Moves (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese National People's
Congress (NPC) today expressed its strong condemnation and
opposition to recent U.S. anti-China actions concerning the Taiwan
issue.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of the NPC Foreign Affairs Committee made
the remarks when commenting on anti-China amendments to the U.S.
National Defense Appropriations Act and on the Taiwan Security
Enhancement Act proposed by the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
A small group of members of the U.S. House of representatives
and Senate have continually attempted to stir anti-China sentiment
by strongly advocating increased arms sales to Taiwan under the
pretext of the so-called Chinese Communist military threat.
</P>
<P>
Jesse A. Helms, chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee of
the U.S. Senate, tabled the Taiwan Security Enhancement Act on
March 24. He was followed by Benjamin A. Gilman, chairman of the
International Relations Committee of the U.S. House of
Representatives, and Thomas D. Delay, majority whip of the House,
who jointly initiated a similar move on May 18.
</P>
<P>
On June 8, the Senate passed an amendment to the National
Defense Appropriations Act for Fiscal Year 2000 proposed by Trent
Lott, majority leader of the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
This amendment openly claimed to "review and evaluate" all gaps
in relevant knowledge about the current and future military
balance between the Chinese Mainland and Taiwan, as well as the U.
S. Defense Department's implementation of relevant sections of the
Taiwan Relations Act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Legislature Condemns U.S. Anti-China Moves (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is known to all that the U.S. side has continued arms sales
to Taiwan in total disregard of the August 17th Communique issued
jointly by China and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
U.S. arms sales to Taiwan have, in fact, increased in terms of
both quantity and quality, including not only advanced early
warning and antimissile system, but also comprehensive military
equipment such as electron-antagonistic surveillance system and a
new type of transport aircraft which will upgrade overall combat
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some U.S. congressmen are advocating Taiwan's
inclusion in the Theater Missile Defense (TMD) System.
</P>
<P>
U.S. congressmen framed the Taiwan-related amendment to the
National Defense Appropriations Act for Fiscal Year 2000 and the
Taiwan Security Enhancement Act with the sole purpose of creating
a legal basis for selling advanced arms, including the TMD System,
to Taiwan and reinforcing military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the move was to support and protect the separatist
activities of some political factions in Taiwan, create tension
and damage relations between the two sides across the Taiwan
Straits, and obstruct China's reunification cause.
</P>
<P>
The above actions totally violated the principles enshrined in
the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, especially the August 17th
Communique in which the U.S. committed itself to gradually
reducing and finally halting arms sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The actions will not only pose severe threat to China's
security, but will also damage peace and stability of the Asia-
Pacific region as a whole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Legislature Condemns U.S. Anti-China Moves (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is known to all that the U.S. side has continued arms sales
to Taiwan in total disregard of the August 17th Communique issued
jointly by China and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
