<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Cancels Oil leases, Causing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has cancelled
16 oil prospecting leases awarded to indigenous operators between
March and May this year, which marks the first casualty of
President Olusegun Obasanjo's contract probe drive.
</P>
<P>
A statement Tuesday from the office of the Presidential Adviser
on Petroleum and Energy announced the revocation of licences.
</P>
<P>
The cancelled leases on off-shore oil blocs were awarded by the
former administration of Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, said the
Guardian, a leading Nigerian Newspaper, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's revocation, which took immediate effect, resulted
from an interim report by the panel reviewing past contracts,
licences awards and appointments raised last month by Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
It was also made ahead of the development of a new procedure
for bidding and allocation of licenses and acreages by the new
government.
</P>
<P>
The leases were accorded this March under the terms that the
benefiting companies were to pay a signature bonus or acceptance
fee of 20 million U.S. dollars (2 billion naira) on each of the
blocs, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Oziko Energy Resources Limited, Totex Oil Nigeria Limited,
Heritage Oil and Gas, Zebra Energy Nigeria Limited, Oil and Gas
Nigeria Limited, Amni International Petroleum Development Company
Limited and a couple of other companies were affected by the
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
The allocations had generated controversy -- largely on the
discretionary basis of award, and were against traditionally
recognized open competitive bidding, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, public opinion rose against the allocation because of
alleged substantial interest of some retired and serving military
officers in many of the beneficiary companies, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
But in a swift reaction Tuesday, some of the awardees protested
the cancellation of the allocations. They alleged that Obasanjo
had made up his mind earlier to cancel the contract, hence denying
them fair-hearing by the review panel.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive of one of the beneficiaries said: "We, at
least my company, submitted a memorandum to the panel. We are
expecting to testify at the panel, at least for the sake of fair
hearing. But nothing came from them. Besides, the work of the
committee is scheduled for completion in three months. Why is the
government being hasty about the decision?"
</P>
<P>
Gen. Abubakar, in a live phone-in interview on the British
Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) on the eve of his exit, was taken
to task by a questioner on the propriety of the award of licenses.
 The former head of state answered that he believed due process
was observed, said the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
