<HEADLINE> Chinese Say Marriage Services Need A More Mature Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua)-- China's Social Economy Survey and
Research Center and the All-China Women's Federation plan to hold
a seminar on developing the marriage service business later this
month in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Research Center's Xing Baojun says that more than 10
million Chinese have married every year in recent years and have
spent more than 100 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars) on candy,
photos, banquets, and ceremonies annually in the process.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a marriage anniversary culture is also taking
root in Chinese society, boosting spending in the marriage
business, Xing says, adding that many people are choosing to marry
this last year of the century, with the most popular date being
September 9, which, when combined with the year 1999, in Chinese
numerology signifies a long-lasting relationship.
</P>
<P>
However, Xing points out, there are no well-established
cigarette or wine brands, or souvenirs, garments, or other
products and services associated with the business, so the seminar
will invite companies and sociologists to jointly formulate a
strategy for developing the marriage service market in the next
century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
