<HEADLINE> Tanzania Stresses Oil Exploration Under Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Oil exploration in Tanzania
is a union matter and the undertaking cannot be left in the hands
of the Zanzibar government alone, Tanzania's Deputy Minister for
Energy and Minerals Manju Msambya has said.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said here Wednesday that Msambya made the remarks
in the National Assembly, or parliament, in central town of Dodoma
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He was answering a question on whether it was the right time
for the government of Zanzibar to invite oil exploration companies
to do the job in the isles instead of having the task carried out
by the Union government.
</P>
<P>
"Oil exploration is a union matter, therefore it cannot be left
in the hands of the Zanzibar government alone to conduct it," the
Deputy Minister said.
</P>
<P>
A meeting aimed at reaching a consensus on the issue was held
in March last year between officials of the Union and Zanzibar
government ministries of energy and minerals, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting formed a 15-member committee to sort out
differences on the issue," Msambya said. "However, the committee
has so far not come up with any solution."
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the Tanzania Investment Center and the
Zanzibar Investment Promotion Authority keep consulting each other
on investment opportunities in their areas through regular
meetings.
</P>
<P>
"The meetings also involve leaders of investment authorities in
Kenya and Uganda," he said. On the oil exploration in Tanzania,
Msambya said an Irish oil company had drilled two wells but no
sign of petroleum deposit could be traced.
</P>
<P>
The drilling was done by the Dublin International Petroleum
Limited of Ireland at Mandawa in southeastern Lindi Region from 26
November 1996 to 18 January 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the Irish company was continuing with the search for oil
within the same area, he said, a Canadian company, the Antrim
Resources of Canada expects to explore for petroleum on Zanzibar
islands.
</P>
<P>
"Though the Canadian firm has signed a contract with the
Tanzania Petroleum Development Corporation in October 1997," the
Deputy Minister said, "Antrim Resources, now called Antrim Energy
Limited, is yet to be cleared by the Zanzibar government."
</P>
<P>
Tanganyika, or the Mainland, got independence from the British
colonial rule on December 9, 1961 while Zanzibar ended the
Sultanate rule on January 12, 1964 through a bloody revolution.
</P>
<P>
The two East African states merged on April 26, 1964 to form a
union - the United Republic of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution, the Union has a president and a
vice- president while Zanzibar is ruled by its own president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
