<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Girls Twice Likely to Consider Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadian girls are almost twice as
likely as boys to consider committing suicide, according to a
latest survey by Statistics Canada.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted for the first time last year, shows that
8.4 percent of the 12- and 13-year old girls had suicidal thoughts
in the year, as compared with 4.6 percent of boys.
</P>
<P>
The year also saw nearly 7 percent of children embarking on
their difficult teen years with serious ideas about killing
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Suicide researchers said the figures give statistical backing
to growing suspicions that young Canadians are plagued with
depression.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Harrington, Director of the Suicide Information and
Education Center in Calgary in western Canada, said that the rate
of death from suicide rose dramatically among very young children
over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1996, the average rate of suicide for children
aged 10 to 14 in Canada was 2.2 for every 100,000, up from 1.2 per
100,000 a decade earlier.
</P>
<P>
The most important influence on suicidal thoughts is a child's
relationship with the parents, as illustrated by the survey data.
</P>
<P>
Children with a difficult relationship with their parents are 5.
5 times more likely than others to consider a suicidal plan.
</P>
<P>
But the survey also shows that 93 percent of the 12- and 13-
year-olds said they were happy with their way of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reception Marks 38th Anniversary of Sino-DPRK Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese People's Association
for Friendship with Foreign Countries (CPAFFC) held a reception
this evening to mark the 38th anniversary of the signing of the
Sino-Korean Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and Mutual
Assistance.
</P>
<P>
CPAFFC President Qi Huaiyuan said at the occasion that China
and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) have observed
the spirit of the treaty by strengthening solidarity, promoting
friendship and cooperation and supporting each other since the
treaty was signed.
</P>
<P>
"This has not only promoted the full development of bilateral
ties, but also played an important role in safeguarding peace in
Asia and the world at large," Qi said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the June visit to China by Kim Yong Nam, the
president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly,
promoted friendship and cooperation, saying that under the current
international situation, the maintenance and promotion of Sino-
DPRK friendship and cooperation accords with the fundamental
interests of both peoples, and is also significant to peace and
stability in the Korean peninsula, northeast Asia and the world as
a whole.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK's ambassador to China, Chu Chang Jun, praised the
traditional friendship between the two countries, and said he
believes that the Sino-DPRK friendship, which was cemented by
blood, will continue to grow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
