<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Mediation over Disputed Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Wednesday rejected any
mediation by third parties between Iran and the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) to settle their territorial disputes over the
three islands in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"We do not need any mediation by other parties to solve the
problem," Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi told
a press conference, adding the "misunderstanding" between Iran and
the UAE should be solved through bilateral and direct talks.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a response to the recent formation of an
ad hoc committee by the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) to help
solve the Tehran-Abu Dhabi dispute over the islands of Abu Musa,
the Greater and the Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi
Arabia and the UAE decided on Saturday to form a committee in
order to devise a mechanism to discuss the UAE-Iran dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman underlined that UAE Foreign Minister
Rashid Abdullah al-Nuaimi should visit Tehran to answer the two
visits by his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi to Abu Dhabi.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the three islands of Abu Musa, the Greater
and Lesser Tunbs belong to Iran and are an integral part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the UAE should remove the "misunderstanding" on the
basis of the letter of understanding signed between Iran and
Sharjah, one of the UAE's emirates, in 1971 to co-rule the Abu
Musa island, Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the islands in 1971 soon after the British
colonist forces withdrew from the region. However, both Tehran
and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty over the islands.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly called for mutual talks to remove
"misunderstanding" between the two countries, but the UAE has
called for international arbitration to solve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, which comprises Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Kuwait,
Bahrain, Oman and Kuwait, has announced its support for the UAE's
sovereignty over the islands and called for peaceful solution to
the Iran-UAE dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
