<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leonean Warring Parties Reach Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The government of Sierra Leone
reached a peace deal with its rebel -- the Revolutionary United
Front (RUF) Wednesday morning to end a civil war in the west
African country.
</P>
<P>
"The two parties have agreed to sign," Togo's foreign minister,
Joseph Kokou Koffigoh, told reporters at a regional summit in the
Togolese capital Lome.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached with the help of five African
presidents currently attending a mini-summit in Lome.
</P>
<P>
The accord was to be signed later Wednesday by Sierra Leone's
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and the RUF leader Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
A rebel official confirmed the agreement and said the rebels'
field commanders have also endorsed the deal, according to
information reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The deal gives rebels four ministerial and four deputy
ministerial posts, a report cited United Nations Sources as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The deal also provided for a "reprieve" from prosecution for
rebels who were recently vehemently accused by some human rights
groups of committing "alarmingly severe" war crimes.
</P>
<P>
The west Africa Peacekeeping force ECOMOG is also to stay in
the war- torn west African state, according to the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
