<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Allowing Foreigners To Set Up Joint Commercial Businesses in More Places </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- China has opened more cities to
overseas investors for joint commercial businesses, with new
regulations from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation and the State Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Pilot Regulations Regarding Overseas Investment in
Commercial Companies were released on June 25 and took effect the
same day. They say that overseas investors can now set up equity
joint or contractual joint commercial businesses with Chinese
partners in the capitals of all provinces and autonomous regions
and some other major cities. Previously, they were only allowed in
Shanghai and Shenzhen and solely foreign-funded commercial
companies are still not allowed.
</P>
<P>
The pilot regulations are intended to increase China's opening
to the rest of the world and reforms and development of Chinese
companies and to ensure the healthy and orderly establishment of
overseas-backed companies on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-backed companies have to comply with the commercial
development plans of the city they choose to locate in and can
bring in advanced sales and management techniques and help China's
commercial modernization drive and export increases.
</P>
<P>
The regulations say that overseas-backed commercial entities
can operate for a period of 30 years and in central and western
parts of the country for a period of 40 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Methods on Overseas-Funded Commercial Businesses for Trial Implementation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Following is the full text of the
Methods on Overseas-Funded Commercial Businesses for Trial
Implementation, which was promulgated on June 25 by the State
Economic and Trade Commission and the Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (unofficial translation):
</P>
<P>
Article One The methods are formulated with a view to further
expanding the reform and development of commercial enterprises,
promoting domestic market building, and ensuring the healthy and
orderly use of overseas investment in the commercial sector on a
trial basis, in line with the Law on Sino-Overseas Equity Joint
Ventures of the People's Republic of China and the Law on Sino-
Overseas Contractual Joint Ventures of the People's Republic of
China as well as other relevant laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Article Two The methods apply to Sino-overseas equity or
contractual joint ventures engaged in commercial business
established in China by overseas companies and their Chinese
partners (hereafter referred to as "jointly invested commercial
businesses"). Solely overseas-invested commercial businesses are
not allowed for the time being.
</P>
<P>
Article Three Jointly-invested commercial businesses must
comply with the commercial development plans of the city they
choose to locate in and they must be able to help introduce
advanced sales and management techniquess, promote domestic
commercial modernization, and help increase domestic products
exports to bring about good economic and social results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Methods (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Article Six: Jointly invested commercial businesses should meet
the following conditions:
</P>
<P>
 Item One: Comply with relevant laws, regulations and other
rules;
</P>
<P>
 Item Two: Comply with the commercial development plans of the
city they are located in;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Methods (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Item Three: A retail business should have registered capital
of no less than 50 million yuan and, in the central and western
parts of the country, no less than 30 million yuan. A wholesale
business should have registered capital of no less than 80 million
yuan and, in the central and western parts, no less than 60
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Item Four: Businesses that have more than 3 branch stores (
except convenience stores, professional firms and specialty stores)
must get no less than 51 percent of their investment from the
Chinese partner. Those that have a good record, whose overseas
partners purchase large amounts of Chinese products and who can
increase exports of Chinese goods via a worldwide sales network
can give the foreign partners a dominant share after approval by
the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Those with fewer than 3 branch stores and those with
convenience chain stores, or professional firms and specialty
store branches, must have the Chinese partner holding no less than
35 percent of the investment.
</P>
<P>
Those in the wholesale business, including retailers doing
wholesale business, must have the Chinese partner holding no less
than 51 percent of the investment.
</P>
<P>
Item Five: Branches of jointly invested commercial
businesses are limited to shops that get direct investment from
and are operated by foreign and Chinese partners. Other forms of
branch stores are not allowed.
</P>
<P>
Item Six: Jointly invested commercial businesses can operate
for 30 years, and those in central and western China, for 40 years.
More
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Methods (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Article Seven When an overseas partner signs a contract with a
jointly invested commercial business to allow the use of its
trademark, logo or technology, it can charge no more than 0.3
percent of total annual sales of the commercial business for a
period of no longer than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
 Article Eight The following are procedures for establishing
a jointly invested commercial business:
</P>
<P>
 The Chinese partner should submit a feasibility study that
will serve as a project proposal and other relevant documents to
the local economic and trade commission. The local economic and
trade commission will, along with local domestic trade departments,
submit the feasibility study and other documents to the State
Economic and Trade Commission (SETC). The SETC will then consult
the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation before
granting final approval.
</P>
<P>
 When the feasibility study is approved, the local foreign
trade and economic cooperation department will send contracts and
articles of association to the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation for examination and approval.
</P>
<P>
 Upon getting approval, the foreign invested commercial
business needs to register at the state industrial and commercial
management department within a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Methods (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Article Nine The following documents are necessary for
application:
</P>
<P>
 Item One: Documents for feasibility studies include:
</P>
<P>
First: Documents done by all parties involved;
</P>
<P>
Second: Proof of bank credibility, copy of registration
certificate, and copy of legal person identification of all
parties involved;
</P>
<P>
Third: Annual statement of assets and liabilities and
annual profits and losses for the past three years of all parties
involved, audited by a registered accountant;
</P>
<P>
Fourth: An appraisal report from the State assets
management department on the State assets that the Chinese partner
plans to invest;
</P>
<P>
Fifth: Documents for the items that the jointly invested
commercial business plans to sell;
</P>
<P>
Sixth: other relevant documents;
</P>
<P>
 Item Two: Contracts and articles of association documents
include:
</P>
<P>
First: Documents on feasibility studies and approval;
</P>
<P>
Second: Contracts and articles of association of the
jointly invested commercial business, signed by authorized
representatives;
</P>
<P>
Third: A list of import and export commodities;
</P>
<P>
Fourth: A list of the members of the board of directors
and letters of appointment of directors;
</P>
<P>
Fifth: A letter of prior approval for the name of the
planned business, certified by the State Administration of
Industry and Commerce;
</P>
<P>
Sixth: other relevant documents;
</P>
<P>
All the aforementioned documents, unless otherwise
designated as copies, must be formal documents. Documents signed
by non-legal representative must be accompanied by authorization
of the legal representative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Methods (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Article Eleven When approval is given by the State Economic
and Trade Commission, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation will examine the application of a jointly invested
commercial business wanting to engage in wholesale business,
establish branches, or change business partners.
</P>
<P>
An application for any other changes must be submitted to the
office where the original approval was given in accordance with
regulations on overseas-invested enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, the jointly invested commercial business must
submit the following documents:
</P>
<P>
 First: An application;
</P>
<P>
 Second: Reports on business operations;
</P>
<P>
 Third: Reports on capital verification;
</P>
<P>
 Fourth: Reports on export;
</P>
<P>
 Fifth: Resolutions made by the board of directors;
</P>
<P>
 Sixth: Contracts and revised articles of association; and
</P>
<P>
 Seven: Other relevant documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Methods (8) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Article Twelve Scope of operations of jointly invested
commercial business:
</P>
<P>
 Item One: For retailers:
</P>
<P>
 First: Retail businesses, including those operating on a
commission or trust basis;
</P>
<P>
 Second: Domestic product export;
</P>
<P>
 Third: Import and export; and
</P>
<P>
 Fourth: Foreign trade services.
</P>
<P>
 Item Two: For wholesalers:
</P>
<P>
 Wholesale of domestic products and imported products on the
domestic market, and exports of domestic products.
</P>
<P>
Article Thirteen With an approval, jointly invested commercial
businesses engaged in retail business can get involved in
wholesale business.
</P>
<P>
Article Fourteen Jointly invested commercial businesses are
not allowed to act as import and export agents.
</P>
<P>
Article Fifteen When dealing in goods that are covered by
special regulations or quotas or certificates, jointly invested
commercial businesses must go through examination and approval
procedures.
</P>
<P>
Annual imports of jointly invested commercial businesses are
not to exceed 30 percent of the gross sales of the same year.
</P>
</TEXT>
