<HEADLINE> Cambodia to Build 1st International Standard Jetty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Sokimex Cambodian
Investment Co. Ltd. signed an investment deal Wednesday with
Japanese Marubeni Corporation on the construction of a jetty in
Sihanoukville, 230 kilometers from here.
</P>
<P>
"This cooperation project to be taken by the Sokimex Cambodia
Investment Co. Ltd. and Marubeni is the first large-scale joint
venture" between the two countries, Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen noted.
</P>
<P>
"The construction of an international standard Sihanoukville
petroleum port will make great contribution to addressing the
infrastructure constraints facing our country in the new
millennium," he added.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to accommodate a wide range of vessels,
from small coastal tankers of 5,000 tons to larger ones of 30,000
tons tankers with a length of more than 180 meters, according to
Sok Na, director general of Sokimex.
</P>
<P>
Sokimex is a local company established in 1991 for its
petroleum business in Cambodia. It has five petroleum depots with
a total capacity of 120,000 cubic meters to serve all its service
stations and industrial customers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The project requires a capital of 10 million U.S. dollars of
which 80.5 percent will be provided by Sokimex and 19.5 percent
by Marubeni. The construction is to commence this month and to be
completed by mid-2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
