<HEADLINE> Philippines' Watersheds in Critical Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Around 90 percent of the watersheds
in the Philippines are by now categorized as hydrologically
critical due to their degraded ecological conditions, the
Department of Natural Resources and Environment (DENR) said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, DENR Secretary Antonio Cerilles identified at a
meeting 16 watershed areas that will be initially rehabilitated
and managed on the basis of the Watershed and Ecosystem Planning
and Management Framework approach.
</P>
<P>
Cerilles explained that the framework is a holistic,
multiple-use and sustainable management of all the resources
within a spatial unit known as a watershed.
</P>
<P>
"This framework provides for the management of all physical
assets found within a watershed including soil, water, timber and
non-timber products, as well as the people living in the area or
are affected therein, in a way that is environmentally sound,
economically viable and socially acceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cerilles added that the framework is intended to arrest the
further degradation of the country's watersheds while enhancing
yield of high-quality water and restoring their other productive
and protection functions.
</P>
<P>
He said the DENR embarked on the framework "to prevent water
shortages, protect the country's food security by sustaining water
withdrawals of farmers through irrigation systems and to sustain
and increase the life span of the country's hydro-electric
projects."
</P>
<P>
Local annual water withdrawal has been estimated at 29.5 cubic
kilometers with agriculture accounting for 62 percent, industry 27
percent and domestic use 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
There are around 119 proclaimed watersheds in the Philippines
comprising some 419 river basins, which provide the major water
requirements of several irrigation systems, hydro-electric dams
and domestic and industrial water systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
