<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Membership Fee Arrears Affect OAU Operations: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The delay in payment of membership
fees has greatly affected the normal operations of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), a senior official with the
continental organization said here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, OAU spokesman Ibrahim
Gagash said the arrears have shot up to 49 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Nine member states now suffer from sanctions by the OAU
because they have not paid their fees for at least two years," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged these countries to pay their overdue membership fees
to help the organization out of the current financial difficulty.
</P>
<P>
"There are more countries more committed to the OAU, but the
financial problem is the prime impediment to the operations of the
departments within the 36-year-old African political bloc," Gagash
added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said OAU's financial problem is high on the
agenda of the two-day ambassadorial meeting, which opened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Driven by lack of fund and aspiration for high efficiency, the
organization is currently restructuring itself through an 18-month
program which is scheduled to complete by end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the restructuring project will not
affect the five deputy secretaries-generals of the OAU, because
they were elected and come from five different geographical
regions of the continent.
</P>
<P>
At present, a total of about 600 staff members, including 152
of the professional category recruited from over 41 member states
are in the service of the organization at the headquarters in
Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, and other regional and sub-regional
offices.
</P>
<P>
The OAU was founded on June 25 of 1963 to promote unity and
solidarity among African states, to coordinate and intensify
cooperation, defend their sovereignty and to enhance international
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
