<HEADLINE> Anelka to Seek Help from French Federation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 7 (Xinhua) -- French talented striker Nicolas Anelka
is mulling about turning to his national soccer federation for
help in his resolute bid to leave English Premier side Arsenal for
Italian club Lazio.
</P>
<P>
The Italian press said on Wednesday that Anelka has a legal
team working on the case and that they are prepared to ask the
French Football Federation for help in freeing the 20-year-old ace
from a contract with the Gunners which runs until 2003.
</P>
<P>
Anelka has said he would prefer to join Spanish first division
Real Madrid than Lazio but would rather play for the Rome side
than stay at Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
However, club bosses David Dein and Sergio Cragnotti have
failed to find common ground over the transfer price.
</P>
<P>
Italian news agency ANSA said the sticking point was a 12
billion lire (6.34 million U.S. dollars) discrepancy between
Arsenal's asking price and Lazio's offer.
</P>
<P>
English newspapers reported last month that Arsenal had sought
28 million pounds (44.60 million U.S.dollars) for Anelka in what
would be a world record for a straight cash transfer.
</P>
<P>
Anelka's lawyers would be willing to take the case to the
European Court, arguing that Arsenal were preventing the free
circulation of workers within the European Union, according to
local reports. 
</P>
