<HEADLINE> Manila Forms Task Force to Help Farmers Near Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- In anticipation of an eruption of
the Mayon volcano in the central Philippines, Agriculture
Secretary Edgardo Angara Wednesday announced the formation of a
task force that would focus on the plight of farmers who might be
displaced.
</P>
<P>
Angara said the task force has already begun listing farmers in
seven endangered villages where crops, livestock and
infrastructure are expected to be affected by an eruption of the
volcano in Albay Province.
</P>
<P>
He said the Agriculture Department has assigned a volunteer
group who will assist the evacuees in obtaining food, maintaining
sanitation and disseminating information.
</P>
<P>
The department has also lined up necessary actions for farmers
after the possible eruption of Mayon, including the distribution
of seeds, plant materials and livestock, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Angara, the department will coordinate with the
local government units in case some farmers are relocated in areas
where they can start farming immediately.
</P>
<P>
"We are closely monitoring the developments in the volcano's
activity to further implement the disaster plans for our Albay
farmers who mainly depend on our agricultural resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
Alert 2 is still being maintained within a seven-kilometer
danger zone of Mount Mayon which started activity on June 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
