<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Get Aid for Power Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has received a commitment
of 80 million U.S. dollars from Germany and Japan for the
improvement of its power sector, the national news agency BSS
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the committed 80 million dollars, the KFW, a donor agency in
Germany, will provide 72 million dollars for overhauling three
units of a power plant while the rest 8 million dollars will come
from the Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund of Japan for another
two power plants, official sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government had sought 140 million dollars from
the donors for the rehabilitation of some of the existing old and
junk power plants to recover at least 300 megawatts of power.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the Asian Development Bank were asked to
provide the remaining 60 million dollars, but they put forward
certain conditions including incorporating the power stations and
handing over the transmission lines to the Power Grid Company
before committing the fund.
</P>
<P>
Extensive discussions are going on with the donors to get the
remaining portion of the fund for rehabilitating the power plants.
</P>
<P>
The government has also initiated discussions with Canada and
Italy for 15 million dollars for overhauling four other power
plants.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the overhauling work of the other existing power
plants is expected to recover 643 megawatts of power by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh's existing 19 power plants are
generating 2,290 megawatts of power and 17 out of the 56 units of
these power plants remain closed due to a lack of repair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
