<HEADLINE> Taliban Leader Shrugs Off U.S. Economic Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The supreme leader of the ruling
Taliban in Afghanistan, Mulla Muhammad Omar Mujahid, Wednesday
shrugged off U.S. economic sanctions against his organization,
saying his people do not care about this.
</P>
<P>
The News Network International, a private news agency here,
quoted Omar as saying Washington has slapped sanctions on the
militia because "we are the hurdle in the way of U.S. nefarious
designs in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
"If the issue of Osama bin Laden led to the imposition of
economic sanctions, let us make it clear that he had been living
in Afghanistan since long, but why didn't Washington raise
objection to his presence in Afghanistan?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"Why didn't the Americans demand Osama from the previous Afghan
regimes," said the leader of the Taliban, which control 90 percent
of the war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Osama, a Saudi millionaire, had been in Afghanistan from the
late 1970s to the 1980s fighting against the Soviet invasion.
After being accused by the United States of masterminding the bomb
attacks on the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last August,
Osama left his dwelling in the southern Afghan city of Kandahar in
February this year.
</P>
<P>
"The United States wants to show that it can do whatever it
wants as it is a mighty and powerful country and the entire world
is well aware of the injustice being done by the United States,"
Omar said.
</P>
<P>
He argued that he has no knowledge of Osama's whereabouts,
adding that the Taliban have not asked him to leave Afghanistan or
to stay.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that Osama is still in Afghanistan and receiving
support from the Taliban, U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday
signed an executive order imposing trade and economic sanctions on
the militia.
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. officials, the sanctions, however, will not
be applied on humanitarian aid and health services in
Afghanistan. The impacts of the sanctions will probably be modest
as U.S. trade with Afghanistan totaled a mere 24 million dollars
in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
