<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign-Funded Firms Get More Access To Chinese Currency Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC)
has decided to make it easier for overseas-funded companies in
China to get renminbi loans.
</P>
<P>
According to an official at China's central bank, the new
policy will go into effect on July 15. It allows overseas-funded
firms to borrow runminbi loans from authorized local foreign
exchange banks in a simpler and easier way.
</P>
<P>
A foreign-funded company no longer needs to provide information
about its debts or security for the loans. Specific requirements
for ratings at a foreign bank who secures the loan will be
canceled and the Chinese foreign exchange bank will take its own
responsibility for assessing the risk of loans.
</P>
<P>
The new policy allows foreign-funded enterprises to have more
sources of security in foreign exchange such as borrowing as well
as capital and income under current accounts.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, the debtor is freer to spend the renminbi
loans because the only thing not permitted is purchasing foreign
exchange with the money. The term of the loans has also been
extended to as much as 5 years.
</P>
<P>
The PBOC hopes the new policy can help improve the investment
environment in China and spur overseas investment, the official
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
