<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: EU Officials, Bankers Play Down Euro Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The euro's weakness has dented
consumers' confidence in the 15 European Union (EU) countries as
shown in the latest EU poll while politicians and bankers have
been trying to play down the single currency's trouble, describing
it as "cyclical."
</P>
<P>
The European Central Bank (ECB) is due to hold a meeting on
Thursday to assess the decline in the value of the euro since its
launch at the beginning of this year. But EU officials have tried
hard to calm the fledgling single currency, according to a twice-
weekly report of the European Commission, the EU's executive body.
</P>
<P>
The report issued here Wednesday said Sirkka Haemaelaeinen, an
ECB board member, suggested last week that the euro's depreciation
was largely perceived to be a cyclical phenomenon and not a sign
of structural problems or of a lack of credibility.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) argued in its latest report on "Financial
Market Trends" that investors retain their confidence in the euro
zone despite its current weakness.
</P>
<P>
But in its latest Eurobarometer poll published here on Tuesday,
the European Commission said 61 percent of the EU's population
were in favor of the currency while 28 percent were against during
spring this year. Last autumn, support was put at 64 percent and
opposition at 25 percent. In the euro zone, support for the euro
fell to 68 percent from 70 percent last October and November. The
survey showed the public support for the euro slightly dropped
after its launch.
</P>
<P>
Another ECB Board member, Eugenio Domingo, has suggested that
the depreciation of the euro dose not even pose a serious threat
of resurgent inflation in the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
The EU commissioner for economic and monetary affairs, Yves-
Thibault de Silguy, also reiterated his belief on June 29 that the
10 percent decline in the value of the euro since its launch is
because of growth differentials between the European bloc and the
United States, and the consequences of NATO's air war against
Yugoslavia. He also predicted that the euro has a "margin for
appreciation."
</P>
<P>
The new president of EU executive Commission, Romano Prodi,
warned last month that Italy's membership of the single currency
could be at risk if its domestic economic reform falters. He told
the Italian business circle that costs in Italy were still too
high. His comments had led to the euro dropping to a new low on
foreign exchange markets. However, the new EU head tried to talk
up the euro's value later, saying there was no danger of Italy
having to leave the single currency.
</P>
<P>
German central bank, the ECB's model of governance in monetary
policy, has also expressed optimism about the euro. Hans
Tietmeyer, the current head of the Bundesbank, said the currency
had enormous potential if it was politically convincing. His
successor, Ernst Welteke, echoed his view, saying the euro would
stabilize when the difference between interest rates in the United
States and Europe was reduced.
</P>
<P>
But the euro fell to a record low to the level of 1.02 against
the dollar last Thursday after the U.S. central bank raised its
interest key rate modestly.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Europe believe that the euro's problem is the
contrasting position of the EU and U.S. economies. In addition to
signs of strong U.S. economic growth, they thought the euro was
also undermined by political pressure for lower rates and the
continuing inability of EU politicians to speak with common voice
on the new currency.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the European cental bankers are hoping the worst will
be over by the time the young and weak single currency reaches its
first anniversary next January since it shows no signs of a quick
recovery in a short period of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
