<HEADLINE>   Wedding Invitation Row Causes Games' Boss Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Stratis Stratigis, president of the
2004 Athens Olympic Games organising committee (COJO), resigned
Tuesday due to a row over the invitation of him to the Royal
wedding, the Greek press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Mr Stratigis was asked not to attend the wedding of the former
king's daughter by the prime minister himself. He insisted on
going and submitted his resignation which was accepted," one
official was quoted as saying by reports.
</P>
<P>
A personal friend of King Constantin, Stratigis was given an
ultimatum by the Greek government that he could only attend Friday
's wedding in London of the former sovereign's daughter Alexia if
he resigned, a COJO source said.
</P>
<P>
According to the government supporting daily newspaper Ta Nea,
Prime Minister Costas Simitis, who appointed Stratigis as COJO
chief eighteen months ago, did not want the Greek Republic to be
linked with the unpopular royalty which was overthrown in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Stratigis, who was appointed to the post in January 1998, on
Tuesday cited "personal reasons" for his decision to quit his post.
</P>
<P>
However, most newspapers here gave the royal wedding veto as an
excuse rather than reason for the resignation, particularly as
King Constantin is himself an International Olympic Committee (IOC)
member.
</P>
<P>
Athens 2004 and government officials have previously said
Stratigis has had disagreements with some COJO members, some of
whom have criticised his management style, described as forceful.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unidentified sources, The semi-offical ANA newsagency
ANA reported that Stratigis' resignation was precipitated by
government discontent at the pace of work on the Olympic effort
and a series of delays, notably in the choice of sites.
</P>
<P>
However, Jacques Rogge, president of the IOC organising
committee said that work was progressing satisfactory when he paid
an official visit to the Greek capital in May.
</P>
<P>
Stratigis' replacement is expected to be named in the next few
days with Yannis Manos, Greek Bank Union secretary, tipped as the
main contender. 
</P>
</TEXT>
