<HEADLINE> Russian Governor Rejects Yeltsin's Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Governor of West Siberia's Kemerovo
region, Aman Tuleyev, on Wednesday rejected the Order of Honor
award granted by President Boris Yeltsin in protest over "the low
quality of life of the population."
</P>
<P>
Tuleyev said his refusal to accept the award, bestowed Monday,
had been motivated by the fact that for many years he had
expressed "disagreement with the course of reforms that resulted
in the low quality of life of the population," the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot accept the award, when many people do not get their
earned wages, when more people die than are born in the country,
and when the brain of the nation -- its education and healthcare
system -- is paralyzed," Tuleyev said.
</P>
<P>
The governor was the second person to reject Yeltsin's awards
since last December, when Russian writer Alexander Solzhenitsin, a
Nobel Laureate, rejected Yeltsin's offer of an Order of St. Andrew
the First Summoned on the occasion of his 80th birthday.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot accept an award from the authorities that have
brought the country to its current disastrous position,"
Solzhenitsin said during the birthday party.
</P>
<P>
He also refused to accept the Nobel Prize in 1970, but later
changed his mind and picked up the prize in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0342 </DOCNO>
