<HEADLINE> UK Opposition Calls for Inquiry Into NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- British opposition Conservatives
have called for an independent inquiry into evidence that NATO's
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia was far less effective than
the military alliance had claimed during the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Their demands was rejected by the British government on
Wednesday, a BBC report said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Downing Street said the government has no
intention of holding an inquiry because the air campaign had
achieved its goals.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the Ministry of Defense would carry out its
own internal review of operations.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives have cited reports that only 13 Yugoslav
tanks were destroyed during the conflict out of some 300 deployed
in Kosovo as evidence that many bombs missed their targets.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that the allied air campaign inflicted only light
damage on the Serbs' defenses.
</P>
<P>
The Serb forces withdrew "virtually unscathed" from Kosovo and
NATO to a large extent failed to achieve its goals of saving the
Albanian population, they said.
</P>
<P>
Their calls for an inquiry were backed by senior military
figures, including two former chiefs of defense staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
