<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missing Bodies Found in China's Mt. Meili </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, China, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Another four bodies of the
missing Japanese climbers from the Sino-Japan joint expedition
eight years ago has been discovered in Mount. Meili of Southwest
China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The missing bodies and remains were initially found at the end
of June by local villagers who were grazing at the height of more
than 3,700 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
A eight-member searching team, which composed of experts from
Yunnan Physical Culture and Sports Bureau and Kyoto University of
Japan set off on June 30 to the scene where they gathered 100
kilograms of remained bones of bodies.
</P>
<P>
Judging from the remained bones, the searchers concluded that
they were the Japanese members of the joint expedition who missed
from an accident on January 3, 1991.
</P>
<P>
The 17-member climbing team, including 11 Japanese and six
Chinese, made an attempt at the virgin Mt. Meili but never came
back in a heavy snowfall in the 6,740-meter mountain.
</P>
<P>
Mt. Meili was yet to be scaled by any mountaineering
expeditions. The Sino-Japan expedition has tried three times in
1989, 1991, and 1996 but all came to no avail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
