<HEADLINE> College Entrance Examination in Flood-Hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 31,000 high school
graduates in the flood-hit areas in east China's Zhejiang Province
today attended the annual national entrance examination which will
select elite students for China's colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
The examination, which makes the whole nation the world's
biggest examination hall from July 7-9, began all over the country
at 9:00 am this morning.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts made by the provincial government and
educational department, the students from the Hangjiahu Lake area,
which is being severely ravaged by floods since early June,
attended the examination timely.
</P>
<P>
The abnormal rainstorms over the past month have caused a
rainfall three times more than normal years. The water level of
the lake reported a record in history. Many cities and counties
around the lake were flooded.
</P>
<P>
To promise the students in flood-hit area a successful
attending to the examination, the provincial and city governments
have made effort to arrange services of transportation, health
care, communications and lodging for the students.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, many local enterprises or hotels volunteered
to provide the students free meals and lodging as well as other
services to ensure them a good environment to take the examination.
</P>
