<HEADLINE> South Africa to Pursue Peace Agenda for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will continue to
vigorously pursue the agenda for peace and conflict resolution on
the continent, Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said this before leaving for Algiers, where he will lead
the South African delegation to the 70th Ordinary Session of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Council of Ministers this
week.
</P>
<P>
Pahad leads the South African delegation on behalf of Foreign
Minister Nkosazana Zuma, who is currently involved in the Lusaka
talks on Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
South Africa will submit a proposal on ways to curb the illicit
spread of small arms and light weapons to the Council of
Ministers, the Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The illegal spread of these weapons not only fuels violence
and criminality but also impedes social upliftment and
democratization efforts on our continent", Pahad was quoted as
saying in the statement. The South African motion follows on the
successful campaign to ban anti-personnel land mines which the OAU
enthusiastically endorsed, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also recently participated in the drafting of an
OAU convention to prevent and control terrorism in Africa and it
will seek to ensure that this draft text receives the necessary
attention during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, South Africa will table a draft text on the
development and protection of the coastal and marine environment.
The scourge of AIDS and joint partnerships to combat the epidemic
will also form part of the South African delegation's agenda, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the DRC conflict, the Council of Ministers will
also focus on the urgency of attempts to find a solution for the
conflicts on the continent including those in Angola, Burundi, the
Comoros, Guinea Bissau, Sierra Leone, Somalia and the signing and
implementation of the proposed OAU Framework Agreement with regard
to the escalating border dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers will also deal with structural reform
of the OAU and the possible review of the OAU Charter.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers meeting from July 8 to 10 will be
followed by the 35th OAU summit of heads of state and government
from July 12 to 14, when South African President Thabo Mbeki will
speak on globalization and economic integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
