<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece to Deport Large Number of Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece will deport an estimated 500,
000 illegal immigrants who have not applied for a green card to
work or who entered Greece illegally since the deadline for
submissions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greece's Labor and Social
Security Minister Miltiadis Papaioannou said on Wednesday that
immigrants who have not registered for a green card or have
entered the country illegally since November 30, 1997 would not be
allowed to remain in Greece legally.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are an estimated 700,000 illegal immigrants in
Greece. The deadline for submissions ended on June 1, 1998. In
total, 373,196 people submitted applications under the Greek
government's program to legalize illegal immigrants, of those, 225,
691, mostly Albanians, have applied for a green card.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of those figures, some 180,000-190,000 illegal
immigrants will receive a green card.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that 73 committees were now processing the
applications and were clearing 16,000 applications a month. At
this rate, he added, the entire process was expected to be
completed in 12 months' time. So far, 40,000 applications have
been examined and 35,000 approved.
</P>
<P>
To combat crime and provide a clear picture of how many
foreigners were staying legally in the country, Greece began as of
last Friday a nationwide crackdown on illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, some 50,000 illegal
immigrants have been deported from Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
