<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Conservative Parliament Approves Tough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative-dominated Majlis
(parliament) Wednesday approved the general outlines of the new
tough press law, threatening to put more strict rules and
pressure on the country's freedom-seeking press.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Republic News Agency reported that 125 out of the
215 lawmakers in the 270-seat Majlis voted in favor of the
amendment bill to the press law while 90 voted against it.
</P>
<P>
The conservative-sponsored bill was passed after about 200
minutes of deliberations in the Majlis and long-time debates
between the conservative and moderate factions as well as their
media.
</P>
<P>
The new law will force reporters to reveal their sources on any
controversial stories and provide the conservative-dominated
organs with more supervisory powers.
</P>
<P>
The moderates blamed the bill for imposing some restrictions
on the press in contradiction with certain principles of the
constitution, depriving journalists and writers of their social
rights, bringing into control and limit of press activities.
</P>
<P>
They also argued that the new law would lessen the role of the
minister of culture and Islamic guidance, disturb the country's
information dissemination system, harm international prestige of
the country and bring a special faction to rein over the press.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservatives maintained that the bill would help
defend the Islamic and revolutionary values by preventing
outsider's infiltration into the press.
</P>
<P>
Iran's conservative Majlis Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri in
favor of the new law called on the Iranian lawmakers to vote for
the bill in principle and to hold further discussion on the
details in the future.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that the new law was proposed by the
conservatives with the aim of undermining the political and social
reforms started with the election of President Mohammad Khatami
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years, several pro-Khatami newspapers and
weeklies were closed down under the order of the Islamic
revolutionary court, which, in the view of the moderates, has no
right to intervene in press affairs.
</P>
<P>
Moderate pressmen warned that the restrictions imposed by the
new press law would cause more closures of newspapers in the
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
