<HEADLINE> Singapore Works to Attract Foreign Technopreneurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore has made changes to its
immigration rules to let foreign technopreneurs stay longer in the
city state to explore business opportunities, the Home Affairs and
Manpower Ministries announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign technopreneurs who are not yet employed but have a
feasible start-up plan can now stay in Singapore for up to six
months, according to the new rules on the Long-Term Social Visit
and Work Passes.
</P>
<P>
With support from the National Science and Technology Board
(NSTB), foreign technopreneurs could stay up to a year.
</P>
<P>
For technopreneurs who have moved on to start a new business,
the Employment Pass Department will issue Q1 work passes for them,
which have a two-year period and renewable for another three.
</P>
<P>
To qualify, the applicants need the NSTB's support and will be
assessed on their qualifications, funds available and experiences.
</P>
<P>
For a start-up in which a group of technopreneurs are involved,
the Ministry of Manpower can accept team applications for the work
passes.
</P>
<P>
These changes will take effect in September this year.
</P>
<P>
At present, work passes are issued to foreigners who have found
employment in Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
