<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to See Tourism Boom in Near Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will spare no efforts in
further developing the country's booming tourism sector in a bid
to double tourism income within five years, said Turkish Tourism
Minister Erkan Mumcu here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, the 36-year-old minister
said that Turkey enjoys a lot of advantages both historically and
geographically in developing the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Turkey generated 8.3 billion U.S. dollars from tourism in 1998
with over 9.7 million foreign tourists visiting the country. The
tourism revenues were 300 million dollars in 1983, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government attaches great importance to the tourism
industry and has invested an estimated 35 billion dollars in the
sector.
</P>
<P>
High-quality service is crucial to attracting tourists, said
the minister, adding that Turkey has a total of over 317,000 beds
in the tourism sector, including 67 five-star hotels.
</P>
<P>
However, the global economic crisis and the Kosovo crisis have
exerted a negative impact on Turkish tourism, said Mumcu.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the capture of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK) leader Abdullah Ocalan in mid-February had led to an
anti-Turkey propaganda campaign across Europe. And as a result
many western tourists had canceled their reservations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has suffered a loss of 25 percent in tourism revenues in
the first five months of this year compared with the corresponding
period of 1998 due to the above reasons.
</P>
<P>
For the recovery of tourism, Turkey has been launching
promotion campaigns such as inviting foreign journalists to Turkey
which enjoys peace and stability and the move has achieved
positive results so far, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Mumcu added that "now more foreign tourists have been coming
to visit Turkey and the Turkish tourism will be improved in the
second half of this year."
</P>
<P>
In order to develop tourism in the Black Sea, Turkey is
planning to make some joint projects with the United States and
Australia, said the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Belarus Expected to Sign Union Treaty Next Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Belarus may sign a treaty
next fall on the establishment of a union state between them,
Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A program of steps to be taken in creating a union state must
be drafted simultaneously with the treaty in this month,
Stepashin told the Executive Council of the union of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides do not essentially differ on the structure or
contents of the treaty, Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia and Belarus are strategic allies. We will not change
this view," the Interfax news agency quoted Stepashin as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are moving ever closer to becoming a unified state,"
Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting followed Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko's complaint of Russia's slow pace in establishing the
union and threat to get closer to the West if Moscow does not
speed up.
</P>
<P>
The statements prompted a quick response from Moscow, with
Russian President Boris Yeltsin ordering the Stepashin cabinet to
do its best to enter the 21st century as a union state with
Belarus.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the union and the views we shared on events
surrounding Yugoslavia have forced quite a few people to take a
closer look at our plans," Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
Both Russia and Belarus have condemned NATO's 78-day air
strikes against Yugoslavia and the military alliance's eastward
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Most people of both countries support the idea of a union, but
their faltering economies have been a major obstacle in the way of
a single state.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin said trade turnover between the two countries has
been dropping and bottlenecks have been appearing in defense
supplies, transport and energy cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We must focus on important issues and put minor things aside,
" Stepashin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0372 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Deputy PM Says No Disputes Among GCC States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Deputy Premier Prince
Sultan Bin Abdul Aziz said here Wednesday that there are no
disputes among Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) member states and
they are all cooperating to realize their common aspirations.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan, who is also Saudi defense minister, made the
remarks when meeting President of the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting dealt with fraternal ties between the UAE and
Saudi Arabia as well as issues of concern to the GCC countries,
said the official WAM news agency.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan's visit came after the defusing of a friction
between Abu Dhabi and Riyadh over the latter's efforts to improve
ties with Iran, which the UAE accuses of occupying its Gulf
islands of Abu Musa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has always required its fellow GCC members, which also
include Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain, to help
solve the islands dispute first before warming up ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The prince, who arrived here Wednesday afternoon, also said
that his two-day visit was aimed at supporting the decision made
by the GCC to help solve the UAE-Iran islands issue.
</P>
<P>
GCC foreign ministers established a tripartite committee last
Saturday with members from Saudi Arabia, Oman and Qatar. The
committee will help work out a mechanism to start direct
negotiations with Iran over the islands.
</P>
<P>
The committee "is a practical step approved by the leaders of
the GCC countries," WAM quoted Prince Sultan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The prince also "expressed the hope that Iran, the friend and
sister country, would respond to the good and rational intention
in order to establish cooperation between Iran and Gulf states,"
WAM said.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh has stressed that the rapprochement with Iran will
continue, as it will benefit the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammed Khatami made landmark visits to
Riyadh and Doha in May. The visits opened a new page for Iran-GCC
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
