<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economic Zone Reports Good Foreign Trade For First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- China's oldest special economic
zone today released a rosy foreign trade report for the first half
of the year with a year-on-year increase of 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city had 22.3 billion U.S. dollars worth of foreign trade
for the period, with imports climbing up 3.9 percent to 12.3
billion dollars and exports up 15.6 percent to 9.96 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Li Zibin attributes the good growth to the combined
efforts of Customs officers and revenue departments and says that
they have helped reverse a continued fall in export for the first
four months.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen is one of China's most important exporters, with
exports that accounts for 14 percent of the country's total. It
also had 1.35 billion U.S. dollars worth of overseas investment in
the first six months, up 9.2 percent over last year's same period.
</P>
<P>
It also had GDP growth of 13.6 percent to 62.1 billion yuan and
20.8 billion yuan in fixed assets investment.
</P>
<P>
Financial institutions in the city reported 230.8 billion yuan
in deposits and 170 billion yuan worth of loans for the first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
