<DOCNO> XIE19990707.0375 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Strike Plans for WTO's New Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s executive body will on Thursday
detail the negotiating issues it hopes to be endorsed by the EU
trading partners, the July 7 issue of the European Report said.
</P>
<P>
The plans were prepared for the so-called "Millennium Round" of
multilateral trade talks, during which different trade issues like
agriculture, services, environment and public procurement will be
tackled in a single undertaking.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body has proposed a policy document calling
for investment talks to start from scratch without transferring
the results of the aborted negotiations on the Multilateral
Agreement on Investment among members of the Organization of
Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said the EU's Common Agricultural Policy (CAP)
will come under fierce attack during the talks from the United
States and the Cairns Group of agricultural-exporting nations
campaigning against subsidies.
</P>
<P>
But the Commission said it will defend CAP, pointing to the
reforms already undertaken in the EU's Agenda 2000 reform package.
At the same time, the EU executive body also vowed to attack the
United States for its heavy use of 5.5 billion U.S. dollars a year
in export credits for American farmers.
</P>
<P>
The European Union's plans for the new round WTO trade talks
include placing investment, competition and environment on the
agenda of the Seattle negotiations, integrating developing
countries more fully into the open multilateral trading system,
and promoting dialogue with civil society in a bid to improve
understanding of the benefits of the world's trading system, the
European Report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
